commit_message:
Add explanation for installing Python development packages.

Installing software via pip requires the development files
as well. This update simply notes the package names per type
of package being used. Also added a note about extra packages
being possibly needed for building, such as with Tempest.

Partial-Bug: 1367526
Change-Id: I0430c08686012b31073ed98040b5e261a9205ca6

commit_message:
Create _member_ role instead of Member

Horizon moved to role _member_ in place of Member. With this change,
os-cloud-config creates _member_ instead of Member during Keystone
initialization.

Change-Id: Ia4d965335f900e03465f45c701f0bd5a3a4a0ea6

When multiple VMs are scheduled at a time (using --num-instances
parameter), request_spec['instance_properties']['uuid'] is always
set to the first VM's UUID. Thus, basing on this data may be
misleading. In this commit filter_properties are updated with the
valid instance_uuid so that filters and weighers are aware of what
instance is currently scheduled.

Closes-Bug: #1324030
Change-Id: I15db9e26de2331c063805bb22772b6b93fade00c
"}]
commit_message:
Updating instance_uuid while booting multiple VMs

When multiple VMs are scheduled at a time (using --num-instances
parameter), request_spec['instance_properties']['uuid'] is always
set to the first VM's UUID. Thus, basing on this data may be
misleading. In this commit filter_properties are updated with the
valid instance_uuid so that filters and weighers are aware of what
instance is currently scheduled.

Closes-Bug: #1324030
Change-Id: I15db9e26de2331c063805bb22772b6b93fade00c

[{'created': '2014-09-02 19:35:45.000000000', 'message': 'Improve list role assignments filters performance

When listing role assignments, we have the option
to filter them by actor, target and role. The
current implementation uses the standard
filtering the V3.wrap_collection. Given the large
number of individual assignments, this is pretty
inefficient.

This patch allows the controller to pass the
filters into the driver call, so the driver
filter the results itself and as result, then the
list size is kept a minimum.

Co-Authored-By: Rodrigo Duarte <rodrigods@lsd.ufcg.edu.br>

Change-Id: I68a0c657725227fa5b7a14d0184d20e9b378c9a9
Closes-Bug: 1359231

commit_message:
Improve list role assignments filters performance

When listing role assignments, we have the option
to filter them by actor, target and role. The
current implementation uses the standard
filtering the V3.wrap_collection. Given the large
number of individual assignments, this is pretty
inefficient.

This patch allows the controller to pass the
filters into the driver call, so the driver
filter the results itself and as result, then the
list size is kept a minimum.

Co-Authored-By: Rodrigo Duarte <rodrigods@lsd.ufcg.edu.br>

Change-Id: I68a0c657725227fa5b7a14d0184d20e9b378c9a9
Closes-Bug: 1359231

commit_message:
Remove extra tenant_isolation parameter from config file

There was an "allow_tenant_isolation" option for compute and orchestration in
tempest/config.py.  There are no orchestration tests that use tenant_isolation,
removed.

Change-Id: Ifd98ec7df593387d63008ae9aa2bad1a8eb75c9f
Closes-Bug: #1340380

[{'created': '2014-09-06 17:36:25.000000000', 'message': "Volume type needs to be specified when creating CG

When creating a consistency group, the scheduler will find a backend that
supports all input volume types. If a volume type is not provided, the
default_volume_type in cinder.conf will be used, however, there's no check
to see whether the default_volume_type is specified. The fix is to verify
that a volume type is provided when creating a CG (either from user input
or the default_volume_type).

When creating a volume and adding it to a CG, we need to make sure a
volume type is provided as well.

Change-Id: I078d4fdd8d92529e853be16272ad74d1e130f712
Closes-Bug: #1366371

"}, {'created': '2014-09-11 16:36:31.000000000', 'message': 'Volume types need to be specified when creating CG

When creating a consistency group, the scheduler will find a backend that
supports all input volume types. If volume types are not provided, the
default_volume_type in cinder.conf will be used, however, this could cause
inconsistent behavior in a user environment where the default_volume_type
is defined in some places but not in others. This fix removed the use of
default_volume_type for CG creation, added a check to verify that a
volume types are provided when creating a CG.

When creating a volume and adding it to a CG, we need to make sure a
volume type is provided as well.

commit_message:
Volume types need to be specified when creating CG

When creating a consistency group, the scheduler will find a backend that
supports all input volume types. If volume types are not provided, the
default_volume_type in cinder.conf will be used, however, this could cause
inconsistent behavior in a user environment where the default_volume_type
is defined in some places but not in others. This fix removed the use of
default_volume_type for CG creation, added a check to verify that volume
types are provided when creating a CG.

When creating a volume and adding it to a CG, we need to make sure a
volume type is provided as well.

Change-Id: I078d4fdd8d92529e853be16272ad74d1e130f712
Closes-Bug: #1366371

commit_message:
Pass certificate, key and cacert to glanceclient

When glance is configured with ssl nova does not pass it's certificate,
key, or cacert.  Updated the code to pass the certificate, key, and cacert used in the
nova.conf file, if they are set.  Removed nested if statement.

Change-Id: I23fcd070994e435cb42aa09c824d13553503a7c5
Closes-Bug: #1279381

_copy_if_defined expects None for undefined fields.

Closes-Bug: #1370201

commit_message:
Getting rid of explicit 'start-task' property in workflow DSL

* Direct workflow handler now starts all the tasks with no inbound
  transitions so they can be more than one start tasks

Change-Id: I4248692f02a65ca407622bb708017f7bb60256c7

commit_message:
BSN: Allow concurrent reads to consistency DB

Allow concurrent reads to the consistency DB since the
database lock the block was originally protecting against
is gone.

Closes-Bug: #1357102

commit_message:
Allow signalTransport option for sw deployments

Defaults to null (which in turn will cause heat to use its
default) but allows control over software deployment signalling,
in particular to use 'NO_SIGNAL' if required not to wait for success
or failure.

Change-Id: I7b8bb553724173261d9475e2d574fc0e413d2b3e

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-09-09 16:57:14.000000000', 'message': 'Remove Contract on customUserData

A common paradigm with userdata is to supply:
  userdata:
    str_replace:
      template: |
        <some script>
    params:
      param1: value1

With the contract on customUserData being a string, passing str_replace
as the argument results in coercion to a string, which makes it invalid.

Change-Id: I8bcf788522fc2428eaa3c8529ee11b5ed385099b
'}]
commit_message:
Remove Contract on customUserData

A common paradigm with userdata is to supply:
  userdata:
    str_replace:
      template: |
        <some script>
    params:
      param1: value1

With the contract on customUserData being a string, passing str_replace
as the argument results in coercion to a string, which makes it invalid.

Change-Id: I8bcf788522fc2428eaa3c8529ee11b5ed385099b

commit_message:
mkrepo.sh: make sure Packages files are properly sorted

Works around the base system installation failure (the error happens only
with Ubuntu 14.04). Note that the Packages files on Debian/Ubuntu mirrors
are sorted (alphabetically).

Change-Id: I20262e14b90010a67e7fc1d16843313481d0d6a7

[{'created': '2014-05-25 18:37:50.000000000', 'message': "Fix filter rule of hypervisor-servers search api

The response of the hypervisor-servers search api is contained
unintended servers.
The cause is the filter rule of sqlalchemy that is filtered by
the wildcard of hypervisor_hostname, as `%hostname%'.

This patch will enable to search servers by keyword without
wildcard of target hypervisor_hostname.
The api could also search by wildcard, if the keyword is contained it.

Change-Id: If71d1d5edc50d12a8cdf86de8365ce65be0d9be3
Closes-Bug: #1322921
"}, {'created': '2014-05-26 16:15:05.000000000', 'message': 'Fix filter rule of hypervisor-servers search api

The response of hypervisor search APIs:
- /v2/{tenant_i}d/os-hypervisors/{hypervisor_hostname}/servers
- /v2/{tenant_i}d/os-hypervisors/{hypervisor_hostname}/search
- /v3/os-hypervisors/search?query={hypervisor_hostname}
are only support partial match search, not support exact match.
Therefore the result of `nova hypervisor-servers {hostname}`
can include untargeted hypervisor servers.

ex. There are 2 servers exist, test1 and test10. The command
result of `nova hypervisor-servers test1` includes both servers.

The cause is the filter rule of sqlalchemy that is filtered by
the wildcard of hypervisor_hostname, as `%hostname%`.

This patch will enable to search servers by not only partial search
but also exact match of the target hypervisor. The user may trigger
a partial search by including the % character, url-encoded, in the
API call, such as: "/v3/os-hypervisors/search?query=fake%25"

Change-Id: If71d1d5edc50d12a8cdf86de8365ce65be0d9be3
DocImpact
Closes-Bug: #1322921
'}]
commit_message:
Fix filter rule of hypervisor-servers search api

The response of hypervisor search APIs:
- /v2/{tenant_i}d/os-hypervisors/{hypervisor_hostname}/servers
- /v2/{tenant_i}d/os-hypervisors/{hypervisor_hostname}/search
- /v3/os-hypervisors/search?query={hypervisor_hostname}
are only support partial match search, not support exact match.
Therefore the result of `nova hypervisor-servers {hostname}`
can include untargeted hypervisor servers.

ex. There are 2 servers exist, test1 and test10. The command
result of `nova hypervisor-servers test1` includes both servers.

The cause is the filter rule of sqlalchemy that is filtered by
the wildcard of hypervisor_hostname, as `%hostname%`.

This patch will enable to search servers by not only partial search
but also exact match of the target hypervisor. The user may trigger
a partial search by including the % character, url-encoded, in the
API call, such as: "/v3/os-hypervisors/search?query=fake%25"

Change-Id: If71d1d5edc50d12a8cdf86de8365ce65be0d9be3
DocImpact
Closes-Bug: #1322921

commit_message:
Align EC2 and metadata API with rest of nova in get_instance_az

The EC2 and metadata API had their own custom method to get an
instances AZ. This removes this and gets them to use the same paths
as the rest of nova.

Change-Id: I6ff80ce75214959bf7f2c02e6231c58b28600cf0
Closes-bug: #1314490

commit_message:
Throw macro caused syntax error exception

'Throw: something' statement caused syntax error upon class load
(i.e. without even being executed)

Change-Id: I99217dd31c26ca9cd2488fd2510870867d6fe435
Closes-Bug: #1369491

Make sure the name in setup.cfg is murano-agent not muranoagent

This also reverts the following oslo-incubator commit
https://github.com/openstack/oslo-incubator/commit/f6a1848688483c34be2fb5ba2544f80bc659a26c

commit_message:
Refactoring engine using abstraction of command

* Refactored engine completely
* Rearranged utility classes to remove circular dependencies
* Fixed policies
* Fixed workflow handlers to generate commands
* Fixed all unit tests
* Other minor changes

Change-Id: Ie0c4d8222ff701e50876a8fe4660e297fc4bc4af

commit_message:
On lock removal validate that they key was actually deleted

Instead of assuming the lock was released (when it might have
not been) be more reliable and return whether it really was
or was not by validating the reply.

Change-Id: I70b2e1946d5101c7fbbf4ed9f15007bb98e92581

commit_message:
Fix for missing notification in Sahara OSTF tests

Platform test for Sahara can fail if default security group has no "TCP"
rules. In accordance with that the check for "TCP" rules was added
to reduce the number of such failures.

Closes-Bug: #1342639

Change-Id: I083eaac15748422c4b2713ab3a42064d68c12c4d

commit_message:
Add required statement for multipath and E-Series

This adds a blurb to denote that multipath is a required setting for
operating the Cinder E-Series and EF-Series driver, along with the
appropriate configuration options for cinder.conf and nova.conf.

Change-Id: I658c9d73873677cdb069d736f8881cb81597025f

The exact implementation in two ssh commands is due to pecularities of
bash in Fedora 17 used as image for VMs in autoscaling test.

commit_message:
Fix VM load release in Heat autoscaling tests

Make load release command more targeted in killing a CPU loading process
by getting its actual PID.

The exact implementation in two ssh commands is due to pecularities of
bash in Fedora 17 used as image for VMs in autoscaling test.

Change-Id: I9e0b67bffa7a944241f1e15ed92e29b0b6e040dd
Related-Bug: #1361629

commit_message:
Always pass a project_id

Since v1.1, the `X_PROJECT-ID` became a required header. This patch adds
a way to specify the project id regardless of the backend. In order to
pass the project id, it's necessary to pass the `os_project_id` option
in the `auth_opts` dictionary. For example:

  auth_opts = {'options': {'os_project_id': 'yadayada'}}

Partially-Implements blueprint: api-v1.1

Change-Id: If72b758e634dc1e6bc1e1cc0c63361e8a43861bb

commit_message:
Respect queue's lazy creation

Queue's are now lazy resources. This patch removes the `auto_create`
keyword from the queue's constructor. Either posting a message to a
queue or setting its metadata will create the queue server side.

Partially-Implements blueprint: api-v1.1
Change-Id: I4f2f2f240404b2619ba0ee75a99fecd0ad10040e

commit_message:
Use queue_creation to send queue's metadata

Since v1.1, the queue metadata is part of the queue endpoint. It has to
be set/updated by using the queue endpoint. The old set_metadata and
get_metadata endpoitns have been removed.

Partially-Implements blueprint: api-v1.1

Change-Id: I7b5b50529c4591701c62a1fa92dddbae9add6265

an admin endpoint, which means pool's rules apply to them.

Since flavors were added since 1.1, this patch also adds a version
decorator that will help making sure features are accessible just if the
api_version the client has been instantiated with matches the version

    2. If the transport loads the spec for the API version it was

    the whole operation will fail before hitting the wire.

Partially-Implements blueprint: api-v1.1

commit_message:
Add support for flavor to the client library

This patch adds support for flavors to the client library. Flavors are
an admin endpoint, which means pool's rules apply to them.

Since flavors were added since 1.1, this patch also adds a version
decorator that will help making sure features are accessible just if the
api_version the client has been instantiated with matches the version
the feature was added into.

Note that the core module does not use the version decorator. There are
2 reasons for this:

    1. Users accessing the core module should know what they're doing
    2. If the transport loads the spec for the API version it was
    instantiated with. If that spec does not contain a specific action,
    the whole operation will fail before hitting the wire.

Partially-Implements blueprint: api-v1.1

Change-Id: I92dbe417655a9eeefb030481a81a67840a63dd0e

commit_message:
Rename `shard` to `pool`

The server's shard feature has been renamed to pool. This patch reflects
that change in the client library. The patch keeps old `shard*` methods
and functions for backwards compatibility and it also raises a
deprecation warning whenever they are used. These functions will be
removed right after k-1

Change-Id: I842bfbcf075845750bc4fff345086636cc775371
Closes-bug: #1348196

commit_message:
Add support for `pop` implemented in v1.1

This patch implements pop in the client library. Pop is a new operation
that has been implemented in v1.1. It allows a client to remove N
messages from the top of queue. Although pop is a query parameter in the
server, it has been implemented as if it were an action.

Partially-Implements blueprint: api-v1.1

Change-Id: I29b771a6167185033821139bd795311f1a25a5e1

The root problem is that the driver code assumes 'get_guest_xml' is free from side-effects and can be called any time the XML is desired. The driver calls this in a great many places - your proposed patch here is only fixing one of those flaws, leaving many others.

This is why the bug says that we need to change the volume driver class API so that it works in the same way as the VIF driver class API. Specifically, we need to introduce a new 'get_config' method for returning the XML config separately from the 'connect' method.  The get_guest_xml method (or rather methods it calls) can then use this get_config method on the volume driver without having side-effects."}, {'account_id': 8247, 'date': '2014-08-27 15:50:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

[{'created': '2014-08-26 19:07:18.000000000', 'message': "Prevent multiple calls to connect_volume on libvirt spawn

The libvirt driver's spawn method makes two calls to
_connect_volume, via _get_guest_xml and
_create_domain_and_network, which determines the volume driver
and sets up the volume connection. These two calls are not
necessary and creates redundant root wrapped calls (in
the case of iscsi), which can cause poor performance and race
conditions.

The following patch caches the config that is returned by
connect_volume in LibvirtBaseVolumeDriver and its subclasses and
adds a method, get_config, to return the cached copy. It also
adds _get_volume_config to the libvirt driver to return just the
volume driver's config, if one exists.

Change-Id: I5d300f8fe99f714d63d51197dc89f556c3a5d43b
Closes-Bug: #1359617
"}, {'created': '2014-08-27 03:39:11.000000000', 'message': "Prevent multiple calls to connect_volume on libvirt spawn

The libvirt driver's spawn method makes two calls to
_connect_volume, via _get_guest_xml and
_create_domain_and_network, which determines the volume driver
and sets up the volume connection. These two calls are not
necessary and creates redundant root wrapped calls (in
the case of iscsi), which can cause poor performance and race
conditions.

The following patch removes the call to _connect_volume in
_create_domain_and_network, which is used to cache the
device_path in connection_info, and adds the logic to cache
the device_path in _get_guest_storage_config.

Change-Id: I5d300f8fe99f714d63d51197dc89f556c3a5d43b
Closes-Bug: #1359617
"}, {'created': '2014-08-29 19:49:17.000000000', 'message': "Split up libvirt volume's connect_volume method

The connect_volume method in libvirt/volume.py does a couple of
things. It does the host OS integration/setup tasks, and it returns
the libvirt xml. In some cases, only the libvirt xml is required,
and the setup tasks are not necessary.

The following patch separates the setup tasks and libvirt xml return
in connect_volume. A new method, called get_config, is added to just
return the xml config, separate from the connect_volume method.
The connect_volume method will continue to return the libvirt xml,
so that existing functionality is not broken. This way, get_config
can be used to get the libvirt xml without any side-effects, e.g.
re-running shell commands to setup the volume.

Change-Id: I5d300f8fe99f714d63d51197dc89f556c3a5d43b
Closes-Bug: #1359617

commit_message:
Split up libvirt volume's connect_volume method

The connect_volume method in libvirt/volume.py does a couple of
things. It does the host OS integration/setup tasks, and it returns
the libvirt xml. In some cases, only the libvirt xml is required,
and the setup tasks are not necessary.

The following patch separates the setup tasks and libvirt xml return
in connect_volume. A new method, called get_config, is added to just
return the xml config, separate from the connect_volume method.
The connect_volume method will continue to return the libvirt xml,
so that existing functionality is not broken. This way, get_config
can be used to get the libvirt xml without any side-effects, e.g.
re-running shell commands to setup the volume.

There will be a follow up patch, where libvirt's driver.py will
switch over to use get_config and connect_volume will no longer
need to return the libvirt xml.

Change-Id: I5d300f8fe99f714d63d51197dc89f556c3a5d43b
Related-Bug: #1359617

commit_message:
Support reading versions from wheels

This change adds the ability for pbr to read the package version from
the METADATA file as well as the PKG-INFO file. The PKG-INFO file
is present for sdist packages but for wheel packages (PEP 427),
there is a METADATA file instead of a PKG-INFO file.

Closes-Bug: #1369179
Change-Id: I2fe52c846fd88d37a4ab78de87eec9defce1ba0a

commit_message:
Flavor update tool for Ironic

As a part of the process of upgrading from Nova baremetal
driver to Ironic it's necessary to upgrade baremetal flavors'
metadata to refer to Ironic deploy kernel and ramdisk.
This tool allows to do that by specifying the database connection
details and a CSV file containing new flavor metadata in the
flavor_id,kernel_id,ramdisk_id format.

Change-Id: I1afcc7bf6ecd51b308916fa587719241f3cbccd2

commit_message:
Deprecate API_RATE_LIMIT setting for Tempest runs

The default value for api_rate_limit in nova.conf has been False since
Havana per commit cfdc59860ef1482e3b064f90f719ec9e484590ce.

Devstack commit f617a2ddddf7d8f759ff3ca5d66a133b124eeb42 removes the
API_RATE_LIMIT variable.

Since we're not going to backport the devstack change to the stable
branches, this patch adds a TODO in the script to remove the variable
when stable/juno is our oldest supported branch.

Change-Id: I21dbd72f9959a4e3d62c36831df03b351a51172e

commit_message:
Add Hyper-V driver in the "compute_driver" option description

The description of the option "compute_driver" should include
hyperv.HyperVDriver along with the other supported driver.

Conflicts:
        nova/virt/driver.py
        nova/virt/hyperv/__init__.py

Closes-bug: #1347777
(cherry picked from commit b856bc5e348cc69923e3ee815303804323730026)

commit_message:
Support lack of ephemeral volumes for baremetal

The agent driver in Ironic does not yet support ephemeral volumes.
This change allows tempest to test Ironic with the agent driver
by skipping ephemeral volume checks if the ephemeral volume size
is 0.

commit_message:
fix Jenkins failures

- upgrade berkshelf requirement to 2.0.18
- don't use bundle when running the Strainer tests
- add a disabled rubocop job

Fixes the Jenkins job failures related to the Supermarket release.

Partial-Bug: #1348258
Change-Id: I79d9d99b8fd868f23d933bf0d21a718227360550

This is related to https://bugs.launchpad.net/heat/+bug/1319813.

FWIW, I somewhat agree with Zane, in that INIT is not really meaningful as a user-facing state - it's really exposing some of our internal implementation state, which is not valuable information to a user, IMHO.

If you consider the workflow:
1. User requests stack create
2. Stack starts creating
3. Stack is either created or fails during creation

INIT has no meaning in any of these steps, and I think that introducing that state for resources was probably a historical mistake.

Considering how the internal states map to the user workflow above:

1. User requests stack create
2. Heat stores the stack definition to the DB and schedules some tasks to create the resources
3. Heat creates the resources
4. Either all resources are created, or some fail during creation.

I'd argue that, from a user perspective, the stack is CREATE_IN_PROGRESS from the time heat accepts the request to do the creation (e.g when it's persisted to the DB), so probably we should just set that state at step (2) rather than when we currently do, which is step (3)

Interested in other folks opinions on this - evidently ref bug #1319813 Robert sees value in exposing the state, but I'm not really sure if the value is the actual state, or more just visibility of the status (which could just as easily be achieved via creation of several messages during CREATE_IN_PROGRESS steps)"}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2014-09-05 13:27:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Hi Steven, 

Firstly, my assumption is that INIT_COMPLETE is a state where there isn't any work being done on a stack but Heat knows about it and will work on it when it's free to do so. *_IN_PROGRESS state is where there's actual CPU cycles being spent on the stack.

So, it felt like there needed to be a state to tell if a particular stack was being idled around not going into the IN_PROGRESS state or not, imagining a scenario where someone launched a lot of stacks simultaneously and wanted to check the progress and all they see is CREATE_IN_PROGRESS for everything where in reality, the creation process for some stacks are blocked/waiting. Although, I am now starting to realize it's probably giving away very little benefit to be a whole new state."}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2014-09-09 08:20:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

@Sirushti Murugesan: Yeah the reason for the resource INIT state is as you describe - I'm just not sure if the decision to introduce that state justifies a whole new stack state, for the reasons previously stated.  

Ideally I'd like feedback from stevebaker as IIRC he introduced INIT for resources and may have thoughts about the validity of this.  

I still think that exposing "hey we created some classes, but haven't yet created any of your stuff" to *users* is not really that valuable (although exposing the transition in to *operators* in the logs would be)'}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2014-09-09 14:40:53.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review-1

('INIT', 'COMPLETE') is at least as good as (None, None) for that."}, {'account_id': 6899, 'date': '2014-09-10 11:23:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Thanks for the reviews Steven and Zane. Response below.

@Steven Yeah, I'm starting to feel the word INIT is the source of confusion here. I think a more meaningful state would be WAITING_IN_PROGRESS or simply WAITING.

Anyway, I'm sort of convinced/realised that a user wouldn't really care about an *INIT* state. Not entirely sure if operators/admins depend on this status or status's at all. It may be helpful in telling them about a stacks status and whether they want to scale their engine workers more to get their stacks done depending on the above status. Perhaps, they'd have a better way of figuring that out.

@zaneb, we still are persisting the stack here. AIUI, The state transitioning is still going to be similar even when convergence comes into play. So I don't understand how this state would fit better in convergence and not the existing model.

Perhaps, I'll just go with CREATE_IN_PROGRESS to align with the existing expected behaviour. If anyone wants to change it with an even more compelling reason, we could again re-visit this in the future if necessary."}, {'account_id': 6899, 'date': '2014-09-11 16:37:22.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-11 18:22:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified+1

commit_message:
Set the default state of a stack to CREATE_IN_PROGRESS

A stacks status is empty when originally entered into the database.
This leads to returning empty status responses back if the engine is
pre-occupied with other tasks.

This patch sets a stack's status to CREATE_IN_PROGRESS by default when
the stack object is created.

The stack object is only ever created during create and preview and is
loaded otherwise from the database in all the other scenarios.

Change-Id: Iab0892896b398530423bbe6c6a623376bf86590e
Closes-Bug: #1365399

Note sure about this one. It essentially does a separate deep check of most of the guestfs stack, to determine whether to attempt to use guestfs or not. However this isn't a full guarantee it will work. Also if the deep check fails for transient (resource/config/...) reasons, you're stuck without guestfs until service restart.

This is a good  example of the idiom "It's better to ask for forgiveness than permission"'}, {'account_id': 7730, 'date': '2014-09-11 16:24:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

It tries to make the process more robust since currently we don't have a mechanism to fallback to localfs if guestfs is not well configured. By this change we can avoid this kind of error:

    http://logs.openstack.org/04/119104/3/check/check-devstack-dsvm-cells/48c723a/logs/screen-n-cpu.txt.gz

I'm not an expert of guestfs and so I will add danpb and rjones to the review to help us to determine if we need this change and how to make it better."}, {'account_id': 7730, 'date': '2014-09-11 16:31:06.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

@p-draigbrady perhaps I didn't add enough details about why I made this change, if I have understood well the problem happens often of the time with os like ubuntu since we have to use the command update-guestfs-appliance to configure it. A good example if our CI. we don't do it and  the error hit us."}, {'account_id': 1812, 'date': '2014-09-11 17:13:15.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

(3 comments)

Still not sure about it. If it's a common issue then it needs a bug to track.

Note by caching the result, one has to restart nova compute service even after update-guestfs-appliance is run, though I guess doing a full extra check each time would probably have too much overhead.

Would it be possible to have the guestfs attempt as normal, and then fail back to localfs on any issue.
IIRC that's what the code in Essex used to do anyway."}, {'account_id': 7730, 'date': '2014-09-11 17:42:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(4 comments)

> Would it be possible to have the guestfs attempt as normal, and then fail back to localfs on any issue. IIRC that's what the code in Essex used to do anyway.

It's difficult since the error happens when calling 'setup'. An other solution I have mentioned to danpb in IRC is to call 'setup' before the method return the object."}, {'account_id': 7730, 'date': '2014-09-12 07:57:49.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 2.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-12 10:27:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Verified-1

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2014-09-12 13:35:31.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review-1

> Would it be possible to have the guestfs attempt as normal, and then fail back to localfs on any issue. IIRC that's what the code in Essex used to do anyway.

I'm really not a fan of that kind of approach for things in general, because it hides real important errors from administrators. eg on RHEL/ Fedora I fully expect libguestfs to be completely operational at all times. If something breaks libguestfs, it is very desirable that Nova get a fatal error, because falling back to localfs means Nova becomes vulnerable to security attacks on the host from malicious images.

Basically if the libguestfs is installed on the host that I think Nova should use that and error if it doesn't work. Only ever fallback to localfs if libguestfs is not installed at all. So in fact, in this respect, I think trying todo this fallback for broken installs on Ubuntu is also the wrong thing todo. Instead either make sure the gate CI systems don't have a broken libguestfs install, or have a working libguestfs installed.,"}, {'account_id': 7730, 'date': '2014-09-12 14:40:07.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 1812, 'date': '2014-09-12 15:14:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)

So this patch currently trades getting a specific "unable to get libguestfs capabilities" error message for no longer being able to react dynamically to guestfs being setup correctly on the system, now requiring a compute service restart to notice. I'm not sure that tradeoff is correct.

-1 for the new warning on non libguestfs platforms at least'}, {'account_id': 1779, 'date': '2014-09-12 15:36:55.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: Code-Review-1

Although this was an approach I suggested originally, on reflection I don't think we should try this at all. Per my comment previously, we really want to treat failure to launch libguestfs as a fatal error. So IMHO we should just abandon this patch and fix our CI instances to actually work."}, {'account_id': 7730, 'date': '2014-09-12 16:08:10.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5:

(1 comment)

Before we have to abandon this change can we consider something, this patch does a little bit more. Currently when something is wrong with guestfs an error is logged and the feature like "inject_data" is just skipped. This change prevents this case and makes the code more robust, if guestfs is not well configured it returns a fatal error to the operator.

BTW:
After reviewing the current algorithm something is wrong; if the user launch a new instance it will use localfs while we probably have to continue throwing the error (in the case when we are able to import guestfs).'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-12 19:54:46.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Verified+1

commit_message:
disk/vfs: ensure guestfs capabilities

Ensures that guestfs is available and well configured. Also
when checking for capabilities this commit introduces an in-memory
flag to avoid repeating the process if succeeded.
If we are able to load guestfs but something wrong happens a fatal
error is raised.

DocImpact: We should add a not for ubuntu like systems that use
libguestfs to execute the command 'update-guestfs-appliance' for
configuring it.

Closes-Bug: #1275267
Closes-Bug: #1157922
Change-Id: I97b3a23829ea1f3aadfe08ca6448b35010d2f312

commit_message:
Break up the logging around the lockfile release/unlock

To be better able to identify when and where are file lock
breaks when release occurs it's useful to distingush the
different steps of release and independently log them as
unique steps.

Change-Id: I3b605994ca7673e5c97e73821d2ea777117f5f09

commit_message:
Add color distinction for deployed and non-deployed VMs

This patch adds a color distinction between already deployed instances
and on deployed. It is good option for autoscaling App representation
as topology page shows maximum of instances in the cluster but color
allows to understand what is actually deployed.
Deployed Vms are green and non deployed are gray.
Also resize topology page for a full view.

Change-Id: Ie8024b86b9e9a9a88dda77075e3fc8bc81e1a06f
Partly-Implements: bp/topology-page

commit_message:
Fix a test_db_plugin unit test side_effect usage

One of the unit tests didn't correctly use the side_effect
parameter for a mock to return different responses to multiple
calls, which resulted in an extra try-except block and an inline
note. This commit fixes the side_effect and removes the extra
catching code.

Change-Id: Ifa1a6a15025b710ecbba956b5b848e32314cf0cf

commit_message:
Initial implementation of Actions UI

Actions are provided per Component, on Actions tab.
Currently each action is a simple link, after clicking it
user is redirected to the Components page. While any
action is being run in an environment (including deployment),
Actions tab is hidden.

Co-Authored-By: Ekaterina Chernova <efedorova@mirantis.com>
Change-Id: I52c462ef92f2b51f407521e7b8d9b1294de4d53f
Targets: blueprint actions-ui

commit_message:
Fixes Hyper-V volume mapping issue on reboot

Hyper-V does not manage iSCSI mounted passthrough disks
correctly on reboot in some circumstances where disk
number assignment can change, resulting in instances potentially
booting with the wrong volume attached.

Co-Authored-By: Adelina Tuvenie <atuvenie@cloudbasesolutions.com>
Co-Authored-By: Adrian Bora <abora@cloudbasesolutions.com>

Change-Id: I99fa75aaa950de2ada8a03bd23c910c3ff810d69
Closes-Bug: #1322926

commit_message:
Add get detailed quotas to v1_1

Nova API v2 has added the option to get detailed quotas.
This patch implements this functionality in api v1_1

Change-Id: Ifee48244ed7146b50dbe0502311e405ed991e0c6
Closes-bug: #1328966

commit_message:
Updates to CLI doc

This updates the CLI documentation to:
- document the OS_REGION_NAME variable
- add a link to the locatin of the tools/ironic.bash-completion file because
  I don't know how/where the user can get it otherwise

Change-Id: I14fe729630cb9b7da298edcb941087a1fe73d41b

commit_message:
Use dib-run-parts from dib-utils

Now that dib-run-parts has been moved to the dib-utils project, we
need to update diskimage-builder to use it instead of the version
directly in diskimage-builder.

This change removes the old copy of the dib-run-parts script in
the element, adds dib-utils as a dependency of diskimage-builder,
and updates the uses of dib-run-parts to correctly handle the fact
that it is now external to the project.

Requires I0be1f876d0e4a7d38e0d5c6010a552a8ebb158a4

Change-Id: Ia0a0df7784a14c49b5c47ac0b03e6c2602c84b3b

commit_message:
Fix code error in pxe_ilo driver

The following code changes needs to be done for pxe_ilo driver:
- vendor_passthru should be called with **kwargs, instead of kwargs

Closes-bug: 1369545
Change-Id: I03d4773525332be85c0ff941306fb961793748e4

I think we must support upgrade from havana.'}, {'account_id': 261, 'date': '2014-09-03 19:23:36.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

I think the best strategy is to rely on the healing migration between icehouse and juno.
The migrations in the path from havana to icehouse can easily be made unconditional, meaning that they will run only if the tables where they apply exists. This implies the migration has to be executed online, but this is acceptable.

The only drawback I can think of is that upgrading from havana to icehouse will lead to a non-healed, even if valid, icehouse state. I think it's acceptable since if you deploy the juno code, you're supposed to upgrade to juno.

And now I recalled why I initially wanted to have a single configuration independent migration between havana and icehouse."}, {'account_id': 261, 'date': '2014-09-03 22:52:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 5: Workflow-1'}, {'account_id': 8655, 'date': '2014-09-04 07:30:32.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

commit_message:
Remove logic for conditional migrations

This patch removes the logic for handling conditional migrations
and adjusts all the patches where it was used accordingly.

The alembic environment has been update to not send anymore
the active plugins list to migrations.

This patch also removes the vestigial 'options' parameter which
was sent to every migration but always set to None and never
used by any migration.

Implements blueprint bp/reorganize-migrations

Change-Id: I7285e0276b262a9ea5d22c456a5a8cf34c461a0c

commit_message:
Add more information to generic _add_floating_ip exception message

When we fail in some unexpected way in the _add_floating_ip method it'd
be good to have more information in the error message that's passed back
to the caller so they don't have to dig into the logs for the variables
involved, especially since the fixed IP might not be provided on the
request.

We're seeing messaging timeouts in the gate and it'd be nice to have the
error information right up front so we can fingerprint on it in
elastic-recheck.

Related-Bug: #1349590

Change-Id: I7c19c5c1bc5d41a922435d78aca0160c45130276

This is just an extra work to do, not a blocker."}, {'account_id': 3012, 'date': '2014-09-17 12:42:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Add AsyncNsProcess

AsyncNsProcess extends AsyncProcess by capability of running process
inside of the namespace.

Related-Bug: #1243216

Change-Id: I2e77f725486a36f01c3836db35e0a70df7d06a65

commit_message:
Add write ability to AsyncProcess

Adds new method write() that uses Popen's stdin to communicate with
asynchronous process.

Change-Id: Ie82c78f05a04bb74c06e51498c35f34c9efcba48
Related-Bug: 1243216

commit_message:
Migrate test_encrypted_cinder_volumes to tempest client

Migrate the test parent class of EncryptionScenarioTest from
OfficialClientTest to ScenarioTest. And some helper functions are
migrated to ScenarioTest.

Change-Id: I33bcd8d0d787ce67617e6ef07652fe1ca1b7e111
Partially-implements: bp:tempest-client-scenarios

commit_message:
Enable haproxy service in os-refresh-config phase

Haproxy should not be started before os-refresh-config phase (the service
is not configured properly yet).

Change-Id: Id63acf3be8f79fdb436426c9c30a0f3cd9f96747

commit_message:
Add swift-ring element

A swift-ring element consists of the basic swift package and the
swift-ring-builder tool. The purpose of this element is exclusively to create
and update swift ring files. The benefit here is that it may be used on an
undercloud or overcloud controller node without having to install the entire
swift service. Also, updates to a ring/creation of a new ring may be
performed on a single, centralised node in the under/overcloud and distributed
to all the swift nodes in a system.

This is not intended to replace anything in the existing swift element. Unlike
the swift element, it does not require any heat-teamplate which is used to
generate swift rings on the node in question (as well as other things) so right
now any node with the swift element must be a part of the swift rings.
Therefore, the swift-ring element could be added to any node in a system
without any other swift services or presence in the rings required.

Change-Id: I018bdb7a8c6f2f7f83a0a7fb6d27332b6ca266a8

A simple implementation of the ironic autodiscovery ramdisk.

* The ramdisk checks whether the node is already known to Ironic by
  calling /{api_version}/ports?address=$MAC for every NIC on a machine
  (except the loopback).  If associated node is found at least for one NIC,
  discovery finishes and the machine is halted.

* The ramdisk creates a new node, using POST to /{api_version}/nodes
  with the collected hardware information and set the maintenance and
  newly_discovered fields True. The default driver to be used by that node
  is passed via the kernel cmdline "ironic_driver="

  The hardware information collected by the ramdisk are:

  * CPU count and architecture
  * Memory amount in MB
  * Hard drive size in MB
  * Mac addresses for all NICs except the loopback

* The ramdisk creates appropriate ports for every NIC, using POST to
  /{api_version}/ports

The machine is halted at the end of the process.

commit_message:
Ironic auto-discovery ramdisk

A ramdisk to do the in-band auto-discovery of the node and auto-register
to Ironic.

* The hardware information collected by the ramdisk are:

  * BMC IP address
  * CPU count and architecture
  * Memory amount in MiB
  * Hard drive size in GiB
  * Mac addresses for all NICs except the loopback

* The ramdisk posts everything to a special endpoint
  passed as a kernel parameter.

The machine is halted at the end of the process.

Co-Authored-By: Dmitry Tantsur <dtantsur@redhat.com>
Change-Id: I5512d1e4d8ae58d8f8b595abcfeddac7d4901f0f

commit_message:
db: Add @_retry_on_deadlock to service_update()

Add the _retry_on_deadlock decorator to the service_update() method of
nova's sqlalchemy API.  This decorator is scattered throughout the
sqlalchemy API for other methods that may encounter this error.  The
referenced bug report shows a trace from where it occurred on this
method.

Change-Id: I93b370d6457d2e85493be01a62a76404d228a6fa
Closes-bug: #1370191

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-07-25 23:03:58.000000000', 'message': 'Make Juno migrations config independent

This patch amends migrations added after the icehouse release
and before the healing migration.
Migrations are changed in a way that they are not anymore
dependent on configuration parameters but are anyway aware of
the fact that the database has not yet been healed.

To this aim, amended migrations now will need to inspect the
current schema and cannot be anymore be used in offline mode;
this is consistent with the behaviour of the healing migration.

This patch does not remove the logic for generating and
managing configuration-dependent migrations. For this reason
upgrade and downgrade routines still accept the active_plugins
parameter, which will not be used.

Change-Id: I9d55a01c64ef555b7774099f497c9eea596aea6e
Partially-implements: blueprint reorganize-migrations

commit_message:
Make Juno migrations config independent

This patch amends migrations added after the icehouse release
and before the healing migration.
Migrations are changed in a way that they are not anymore
dependent on configuration parameters but are anyway aware of
the fact that the database has not yet been healed.

To this aim, amended migrations now will need to inspect the
current schema and cannot be anymore be used in offline mode;
this is consistent with the behaviour of the healing migration.

This patch does not remove the logic for generating and
managing configuration-dependent migrations. For this reason
upgrade and downgrade routines still accept the active_plugins
parameter, which will not be used.

Change-Id: I9d55a01c64ef555b7774099f497c9eea596aea6e
Partially-implements: blueprint reorganize-migrations

Just call register_opts in tests

register_opts already registers options for stores as well. Just call
that function instead of calling register_store_opts too.

commit_message:
mock.assert_called_once() is not a valid method

mock.assert_called_once() is a no-op that tests nothing.  Instead
with mock.assert_called_once_with() should be used (or use
assertEqual(1, mock_obj.call_count) if you don't want to check
parameters).

Add a new HACKING rule for nova to prevent assert_called_once()
usage from creeping in.

Closes-Bug: #1365751

Change-Id: I1055093a1c31792b6411a3cd46c80b8bcaaf78c1

commit_message:
rbd: fix chunk size units

A typo used XOR instead of python's operator for exponentiation in the
migration to glance_store (5e8eb74438423a4d6134af964fd522bf0ca78429).
Change it back to the correct operator.

Change-Id: I80ba27137e56b3b7aa5ef232e4d770fd363dd3c2
Closes-Bug: 1370247

commit_message:
Run tests parallel by default

Remove `--concurrency 1` option from tox.ini which would entail
a parallel test execution.
Add @mock decorator to test methods that have mock objects to make
cleanup correct.
Add store.configure() to configure store properly.

Change-Id: I4b58746f6b6ad037fabb29be5ca1d1febcb0cf95

CLI help text for driver-list says "List drivers".
But it will list only the enabled drivers.

Hence the help text has been changed to reflect the same.

Change-Id: Ib68537b69dd0455558656710e8d7df7f2a03ff1f
Closes-Bug: #1298628

commit_message:
fixes help string for driver-list

CLI help text for driver-list says "List drivers".
But it will list only the enabled drivers.

Hence the help text has been changed to reflect the same.

Change-Id: Ib68537b69dd0455558656710e8d7df7f2a03ff1f
Closes-Bug: #1298628

I still think this document belongs firmly with the code. The format and intent of -specs is not appropriate for this document. Although the tripleo-specs repo is lamentably doc-free, nova's says "used to hold approved design specifications for additions to the .. project".  This isn't that.

Most of the -spec headings don't have any meaning here, eg: Launchpad BP, Other End User Impact, Performance Impact, Other Deployer Impact, Implementation, Dependencies, etc.  It's a poor fit.

Ben, I thought this would be better as a spec too, for higher approval burden and central location. Matthew convinced me that t-i is a central enough place, t-i-e, t-h-t et al can link there. When it goes away we can move it, that won't be for some time.

Yeah, I'm totally fine with this living here.  Nobody's going to go looking for style guidelines in the specs repo.

That said, I would definitely like to see these guidelines treated as a spec, either by requiring a spec to add one or just by treating changes to this file as spec changes.  I very much don't want contentious style guidelines slipping in.  If we decide to just treat this file as a living spec document, I think we should add a note at the top about that so reviewers remember not to approve with just 2 +2's."}, {'account_id': 8688, 'date': '2014-08-13 10:02:22.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 13:

+1 to a note at the top about requiring >2 +2s. Is 4 incl. PTL sensible? Or just 4?

I'd rather not require specs to change this, as we may end up with a lot of rather trivial specs. Nova are publishing their specs now, I'd like to see TripleO doing that, so we don't want to abuse that repo simply for its gerrit ACL."}, {'account_id': 4220, 'date': '2014-08-14 01:06:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 13: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-14 14:57:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 13: -Verified

Fair point about the specs publishing, although I think we might be able to avoid that by putting these specs in a different directory (after all, they're not cycle-specific).  That said, I do think it's extra overhead so I'm not in love with the idea anyway.  The only nice thing would be that it's one less thing cores have to remember - hopefully the tripleo-specs review rules are already well-understood, whereas there will be an education period if we treat this file specially in incubator.

I guess that's a long way of saying I don't care exactly how we do it, but I want to make sure we have consensus (for some definition of the word) before approving these style rules."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-14 15:00:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 13: Verified+1

commit_message:
Add first draft of HACKING.rst

Consistent style is a highly-desirable feature of a codebase. There
seems to be a recognition of this in review comments, but there is no
guidance for what style should be consistently used.

This patch attempts to document our conventions. It is presented as a
file in the working tree rather than a spec. This is modelled after the
approach taken in the nova project and others. I expect other TripleO
repos to link back to this file rather than contain their own hacking
rules.

In order to ease the creation of this doc, I have tried to only include
uncontentious guidelines. Discussion on additional items will be most
productive on follow-on commits.

Change-Id: Ice8c36f8d10b289aeebab01a19c6035a1be85422

Regarding Maru's concern, I think there is a possibility to change the default value of the config parameter "enable_ipset" to False. It is more safe to avoid the risk (though I don't see the degrade so far). IMO it is a nice improvement from performance perspective and it is nice to have in Juno, but keeping the default value False might be a good option so that we have a good balance for the stability and the performance in larger deployments.'}, {'account_id': 8788, 'date': '2014-09-13 08:43:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 26:

commit_message:
Adds ipset support for Security Groups

Iptables chain is linear storage and filtering, when iptables rules are
large, the load of l2 agent is heavy, this patch introduces ipset to
security group for improving the security group performance.

Change-Id: I6ff0ac519d0b9034d3bb5270885ed3cc1805674d
Implements: blueprint add-ipset-to-security
DocImpact

commit_message:
NUMA _get_constraint auto assumed Flavor object

We call this code in the API that is not converted to using objects at
the moment, so we cannot assume attribute access for dicts.

We also make sure that tests exercising it will fail by using dicts
exclusively until the code is converted to objects.

Change-Id: I6fb7104de5522c51f4706c973d8d8d8697d92b31
Closes-bug: #1369502

commit_message:
Remove unused oslo.config import

Commit 46e88320e6e6231550f3e2b40312c51f55e059f5 added
the oslo.config import in one of it's patch series but
in the revision that was ultimately merged, the import
was no longer used - but we forgot to remove the import.

This cleans that up.

Change-Id: I3fcfdab625be68a19162b5053ad4f6f180a72a4d

- check-devstack-dsvm-cells http://logs.openstack.org/46/116046/2/check/check-devstack-dsvm-cells/c867d96 : SUCCESS in 17m 58s'}, {'account_id': 4571, 'date': '2014-08-23 01:08:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

Isn't the stack owner displayed in the stack-show command?

I would guess that this is enough, and that the majority of users are not interested in seeing the owner in the list."}, {'account_id': 9189, 'date': '2014-08-25 14:59:39.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

When I first started writing this patch, my idea was to display stack_owner only when using ``--global-tenant``.  

However, I remembered that, when writing this [1] other patch, it also started as a patch only for ``--global-tenant`` and folks on IRC mentioned it would be useful to have it displayed at all times on the API. [2]

Back to this patch and with this in mind, should I just change this one to display stack_owner only on --global-tenant, then?


[1]: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/101657/

[2]: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/101657/1..4/heat/api/openstack/v1/views/stacks_view.py'}, {'account_id': 4328, 'date': '2014-08-26 11:21:24.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

I agree with Steve, I'd prefer the stack-list output to remain terse by default, with the option to make it more detailed by adding options and/or displaying information conditionally based on the switches passed by the user.

So I'd be +1 on adding owner only when --global-tenant is selected, perhaps also with a --show-owner option for those who want the additional info for non-global stack lists.

Also, Anderson can you please clarify - are we getting the username or a user UUID back here?  stack_owner in stack-show gives a username, which of course won't necessarily be unique over all projects, so in --global-tenant mode will we also get the project ID (again, this can't be a name, or it won't necessarily be unique in a multi-domain environment..)"}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2014-08-28 20:07:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I think we at least want a --show-owner option to show it when you're not listing across all tenants, even if you don't show it by default."}, {'account_id': 9189, 'date': '2014-09-11 18:07:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I like all the suggestions so far.  I'll change the patch to include a --show-owner option that will default to False but will be turned on whenever using --global-tenant (or when explicitly set, of course).

@shardy: in the current patch, that was just the username, but I see what you're saying, so I'll make it so that when using --global-tenant, we'll also display the project ID as well."}, {'account_id': 9189, 'date': '2014-09-11 19:16:06.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-11 21:34:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified-1

commit_message:
Display stack owner info on stack-list

When listing stacks using the --global-tenant flag, the user is not able
to tell who each stack belongs to.  Furthermore, the problem may also
happen if there are multiple users within the same project.

This adds a --show-owner flag to stack-list to display the stack_owner
information when doing a normal stack list.  This flag is also set to
true when using --global-tenant, including an extra project field as
well, since the username is not unique across all projects.

Closes-Bug: #1359898
Change-Id: Id517be1d147f0b3a72ef7c3f8e4d16c7460477f8

I don't want to turn this into a bike-shedding session about ubuntu/debian, but I don't see any value in changing the status quo semantics of is_ubuntu *at this stage*.

matching is_ubuntu && DISTRO=~(7.0|wheezy|sid|testing|jessie) is ugly but probably the most correct way as things stand.  Personally I'd say go back to matching os_VENDOR for simplicity if others agree.

This is outside the scope of this change, but I don't think a platform can really be considered supported unless it has some sort of CI testing.  The (7.0|wheezy|sid|testing|jessie) in stack.sh as supported platforms is surely not correct.  debian fixes are welcome but we should consider changes with respect to the reality of deployments of devstack"}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2014-08-28 13:43:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

There is more to 'supported' as Ian mentions, regular testing is necessary but insufficient.  As the docs say, Ubuntu LTS and latest release, Fedora latest and N-1 are our supported distros.  Others are allowed within those two families (hence the names of is_ubuntu and is_fedora) but I do not consider them supported in the same sense.  Consider the state of Suse support.  Debian and RHEL are included because they are in the same family, ignoring the parent/child relationships."}, {'account_id': 2888, 'date': '2014-08-28 14:48:01.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 7118, 'date': '2014-08-28 21:10:18.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: Code-Review+2

commit_message:
Detect when Debian is used to launch libvirtd

this patch checks if os_VENDOR is ubuntu to launch
libvirt-bin service. Previously, is_ubuntu() was used, but
this function only detects if a deb packaging is used, so
there were no distinction between Ubuntu and Debian.

Change-Id: I222b71962f49896063910ff2a25e4f57be4bf819
Closes-Bug: 1361260

commit_message:
Stop using standard NotImplementedError to skip tests

This can lead to missing tests if any library we use raises
NotImplementedError itself.

commit_message:
Use a thread safe deque instead of a queue

Instead of using a queue like a deque just use
a deque directly instead, a queue doesn't seem
to add much value when its used like it was.

Change-Id: I515c14bb16e18c4031f446c7176915c94b3fb8f4

commit_message:
Add doc8 to the py27 test running

To ensure the docs are style checked add in doc8 to the
py27 tox environment so that the docs will be checked.

This also adjusts the one issue that was found in one
of the rst files.

Change-Id: Iea38d4ac53d9c5255e0694a840c38b04530890ce

Migrate test_large_ops to tempest client

from official client to tempest clients.

Change inline docs about class fake storage variable

class attribute exists and how it is used and what it
represents compared to a real zookeeper setup.

If for some reason the heartbeat can not occur instead
of failing silently it is better to at least log a message

'}]
commit_message:
LOG a warning if the heartbeat can not be validated

If for some reason the heartbeat can not occur instead
of failing silently it is better to at least log a message
so that operators can investigate the underlying issue.

Change-Id: Ide88314c413afa389d6c039478324d6e47f63e82

commit_message:
Use the more reliable sysv_ipc instead of posix_ipc+lockutils

Remove the usage of lockutils (and surronding oslo modules)
and keep it much simpler by just using the sysv_ipc module
directly.

This adjustment reduces the complexity, test exposure and
API complexity of tooz; removing much of the complex functionality
that was pulled in when sucking in the lockutils module for its
simple (but still broken) posix_ipc logic.

Change-Id: I46db9bda252473317a0f3d65fe0329ac2151f332

It's not a silly question, at least not to me.

As far as I can tell the swift_middleware is rather old and not up to date with modern standards of how to do stuff, but it is stuck in a rather hot path of HTTP requests. If you look at the linked bug, there's some discussion there about some ways to improve it, and I've heard from the guy who has claimed the bug, is ideas is "asynchronous sample publishing by threading" which is the "I wasn't aware eventlet was in the mix" way of suggesting pretty much the same as you.

[{'created': '2014-07-24 18:04:08.000000000', 'message': "Use HTTP headers to count bytes in middleware

The bug at https://bugs.launchpad.net/ceilometer/+bug/1337761
reports that swift performance is unacceptably degraded when
swift_middleware is turned on to publish samples.

There are two possible reasons for why this may be happening:

* publishing samples is itself too slow/expensive
* measuring the size of request and response bodies is too slow

The patchset attempts to provide a proof of a concept for addressing
the second by using, when available, the content-length header in
requests and responses and _not_ measuring the size of responses
when no content-lenght is provided by the proxied server.

The existence of this code should allow for further comparative
testing with swift-bench to see what ought to happen to resolve the
performance difficulties.

Not that at this time swift is generally good at returning
content-length headers when requesting an object from the store (as
content-length exists as a piece of object metadata), but less good
when other requests are made. Presumably this is not a huge problem
as the metrics are primarily oriented towards measuring the passage
of objects over the proxy interface and the size of those objects
will vastly outstrip other responses.

If it is a problem it is quite likely that there is some way to fall
back to the original code (which iterated over the response body to
count its bytes)[1] or to improve swift itself to be better at
providing length headers where possible.

Generally speaking it makes sense that using header values that have
already been calculated is going to be a win over iterating bodies.
If iterating bodies is the only way to calculate the cost then it
is probably best, as said in the comments on the bug report, to do
that iteration within swift itself where the cost can be minimized,
not a piece of middleware.

Note, too, that these tests are quite crufty. Using something like
wsgi-intercept[2] to model actual web requests would probably be
mode comprehensible. Again I didn't want to make that change here as
it would obscure the point of this patch.

[1] That's not present in this code because a) it hid the purpose of
the change too much b) generators make it hard to do cleanly.

[2] http://wsgi-intercept.readthedocs.org/en/latest/

Change-Id: I0cbd40105b1f07a9775a9fc42bde50c233f0b950
Related-Bug: #1337761

commit_message:
Use HTTP headers to count bytes in middleware

The bug at https://bugs.launchpad.net/ceilometer/+bug/1337761
reports that swift performance is unacceptably degraded when
swift_middleware is turned on to publish samples.

There are two possible reasons for why this may be happening:

* publishing samples is itself too slow/expensive
* measuring the size of request and response bodies is too slow

The patchset attempts to provide a proof of a concept for addressing
the second by using, when available, the content-length header in
requests and responses and _not_ measuring the size of responses
when no content-lenght is provided by the proxied server.

The existence of this code should allow for further comparative
testing with swift-bench to see what ought to happen to resolve the
performance difficulties. Casual testing shows that counting the
size of data is less of a contributing factor than publishing
samples.

Not that at this time swift is generally good at returning
content-length headers when requesting an object from the store (as
content-length exists as a piece of object metadata), but less good
when other requests are made. Presumably this is not a huge problem
as the metrics are primarily oriented towards measuring the passage
of objects over the proxy interface and the size of those objects
will vastly outstrip other responses.

If it is a problem it is quite likely that there is some way to fall
back to the original code (which iterated over the response body to
count its bytes)[1] or to improve swift itself to be better at
providing length headers where possible.

Generally speaking it makes sense that using header values that have
already been calculated is going to be a win over iterating bodies.
If iterating bodies is the only way to calculate the cost then it
is probably best, as said in the comments on the bug report, to do
that iteration within swift itself where the cost can be minimized,
not a piece of middleware.

Note, too, that these tests are quite crufty. Using something like
wsgi-intercept[2] to model actual web requests would probably be
mode comprehensible. Again I didn't want to make that change here as
it would obscure the point of this patch.

[1] That's not present in this code because a) it hid the purpose of
the change too much b) generators make it hard to do cleanly.

[2] http://wsgi-intercept.readthedocs.org/en/latest/

Related-Bug: #1337761

Change-Id: I0cbd40105b1f07a9775a9fc42bde50c233f0b950

commit_message:
Improve ODL ML2 Exception Handling

Raise a MechanismDriverError when authentication with ODL fails.
Re-raise HTTPError in "sync_resources" for exceptions whose status code is not 404.

Closes-Bug: #1311758
Change-Id: I99d2c4f270007c369024525ba4e6188d232a0b13

commit_message:
large ops test should be derived from OfficialClientTest

Scenario test_large_ops runs on gate-tempest-dsvm-large-ops
& gate-tempest-dsvm-neutron-large-ops jobs.

This test case boot VM with security grp by requesting the same from
Nova. Nova can behave as proxy in case neutron is enabled.

This is needed to migrate this test from official
client to tempest client as _create_security_group() fucntion
which request nova to create sec grp can not be used via
NeutronScenarioTest.

Partially-implements: bp:tempest-client-scenarios

Change-Id: I7b69811b49caf3aec5983e27862ce955aadf958a

commit_message:
Fix cancel button size in modal dialogs

The cancel button in a modal dialog is being modified by different
css classes than the other buttons "submit/ok/etc.." This is due
to an explicit .close button class in _close.scss. Adjusting that
would have wider ranging ramifications than just the modal dialog
close/cancel buttons, so instead I modified the existing font
size to make it match the submit button, and explicitly set the
line-height to the default (.close has its own line height setting
that doesn't match whats in .btn).

Change-Id: I9f254df8c922105b9fcc9a8beaced639bb2b1d4a
Closes-bug:1359871

(9 comments)

Thanks for thorough review.

Answering the: "why create a separate test for ipset? Ideally there would be a single test class that can be configured to use iptablesmanager or ipsetmanager (since each is essentially a driver for ip filtering)."

I believe it's better to test at this level, because the ip filtering drivers on top of iptables / ipset manager don't work at namespace level. That means that we lose test isolation, we add potential conflict with system IP addresses or other tests running.

I don't mean it's impossible, so probably it's worth thinking about it for K.'}, {'account_id': 8788, 'date': '2014-09-10 06:16:07.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@marun: Looking at the IptablesFirewallDriver, I like the idea of testing over a a more generic "FirewallDriver", we'd just need to add support for namespaces in the IptablesFirewallDriver. It would need some work, and we could test one level up in the stack. I agree it's a better path than individual testing of both managers. Let's look at that after this patch is in a good condition, so we at least have something ready before FFE end.'}, {'account_id': 8788, 'date': '2014-09-10 06:16:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Patch Set 2 was rebased'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-10 07:36:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified-1

Add functional testing to ipset_manager

it works as expected in combination with iptables matching.

commit_message:
XenAPI: often only uuids are used from walk_vdi_chain

WIP - do not merge.

We can improve the performance of walk_vdi_chain a lot by skipping calls
to get the full VDI record when not used.

Change-Id: I7fde3913376260d82bd4f079abee0f63cd87e86f

commit_message:
Import modules for fake IPMINative/iBoot drivers

The fake IPMINative and iBoot drivers are not attempting to import the
necessary Python modules for proper operation.
To fix the issue, this patch attempts to import 'pyghmi' for the fake
IPMINative driver and 'iboot' for the fake iBoot driver. If the module
that is attempted to be imported is not available, then a
DriverLoadError is raised.

Change-Id: I5085a45c867c339ef900d89b5c830467398b3db1
Closes-Bug: 1362114

Thanks Steve.  Making the environment optional should be straightforward and I will add support for that in a separate patch.  For reusing the template, it's a bit more complicated since we have to add a column in the DB stack table and code to manage it.  This is because the raw template stored in the DB is no longer guaranteed to be the original copy.  I asked for opinion on the mailing list last month and Clint felt that the user should manage the templates outside of Heat using something like CVS. I have some initial code but have not proceeded further based on Clint's feedback. commit_message:
Pass list of parameters to engine service to reset

For stack-update, a new argument named clear-parameters with
a list is passed in from the CLI and the new PATCH ReST API
to delete the indicated parameters from the existing parameters
in the DB, allowing the default parameters in the template to
be used.  A new method in environment handles the reset.

Partially-implements: blueprint troubleshooting-low-level-control
Partial-Bug: 1224828
Change-Id: Ia1270b679f27e264e6977c590d676b947c74c5da

subject: ignore .idea folder in heat
messages:
[{'account_id': 8874, 'date': '2014-08-28 09:06:22.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 1633, 'date': '2014-08-28 09:12:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

IMO, this is not really required. You can get rid of it by having a .gitignore file inside the .idea directory and have it ignore everything (regex '*')."}, {'account_id': 9542, 'date': '2014-08-28 09:17:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I also think that tooling files belong to the developer's own global git ignore file, not the project one."}, {'account_id': 8874, 'date': '2014-08-28 09:24:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I think we always directly import project code into JetBrains PyCharm(or Eclipse), and don't like to manually do config for ignore .idea folder.

Project nova and cinder add .idea to their .gitignore file in order to let stackers work more convenient and reduce the possibility of submitting error files in patches.

Although "ignore .idea folder in heat" is optional, it could help stackers reduce the work to configure their git env.'}, {'account_id': 6577, 'date': '2014-08-28 09:28:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

I against this idea, previously we have similar patch for .swo files from vim. So if you use some IDE or another thing to develop you should use your own environment instead of changing in heat repository'}, {'account_id': 9542, 'date': '2014-08-28 09:28:29.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

My view is that whatever tooling/IDE you are using, you use it not only for Heat, and never want auxillary files to be versioned anyway. So why do it on per-project basis?'}, {'account_id': 8537, 'date': '2014-08-28 09:29:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

Good to have. Nova has it BTW.'}, {'account_id': 6577, 'date': '2014-08-28 09:46:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

Look conversation for this patch https://review.openstack.org/#/c/58933/'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-28 10:18:16.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
ignore .idea folder in heat

If we use JetBrains PyCharm as python develop tool, JetBrains PyCharm
would automatically generate its config folder name .idea in the root
dir of your python code.
Many Code projects, such as nova and cinder, have ignore .idea folder.
Project heat should also ignore .idea folder.

Closes-Bug: #1362482
Change-Id: Ifcc87458e4b01743b5a39fad8ac1781af3021ebc

Downgrades the log message when an http request fails from error
to debug. The logging level changed in the http.py upgrade in
I09f70eee3e2777f52ce040296015d41649c2586a which effectively reverted
a similar fix commited in I6d0efb53d1e81adf309f7fa580ec5a8073a811c5.

We don't want to log at ERROR level because we already have an

error log. This results in a lot of noise in the nova log file.

commit_message:
Downgrade log message for http request failures

Downgrades the log message when an http request fails from error
to debug. The logging level changed in the http.py upgrade in
I09f70eee3e2777f52ce040296015d41649c2586a which effectively reverted
a similar fix commited in I6d0efb53d1e81adf309f7fa580ec5a8073a811c5.

We don't want to log at ERROR level because we already have an
exception raised and the caller can handle it if wants
to. However this error will appear regularly in the Nova logs
under normal behavior (say a client specifies an image which does
not exist) and there is no way of disabling only the glanceclient
error log. This results in a lot of noise in the nova log file.

Change-Id: Iec13bff439073a79cb24e9b22fd43603ae4e61b7

After some more digging around, I realized that you're adding the slug getter to the DATATABLE class, which is not a view, so slug here doesn't quite make sense. The intention of slug was to generate an object's url.

What you're really doing here is slugifying the table's NAME. So slug is not a property of the class, but rather a method to slugify the table's name. 

So the easy fix here is to simply name the slug getter to slugify_name or something similar."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-21 21:50:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

[{'created': '2014-04-23 18:36:57.000000000', 'message': "Filter does not work when table name has spaces

Problem Description:

  When the DataTable name (as defined in the 'name' field of the
  Meta class in tables.py) has blank space, filters defined on that
  table using FilterActions wont work.

Cause:
    -table name is used as the table id in the html
    -the table selector used in the quicksearch plugin has the
     following format:
	 table#<table id> tbody tr

     For example: if the table name specified in the Meta class of
     tables.py is 'foo bar', then the table selector will be:
         table#foo bar tbody tr.

Solution:
    Updated the table selector to have the following format:
         table[id='<table id>'] tbody tr

Change-Id: I9d7c0ea3519c8bebb2f1ac5831cb271557908ba9
Closes-Bug: 1311789

commit_message:
Filter does not work when table name has spaces

Problem Description:

  When the DataTable name (as defined in the 'name' field of the
  Meta class in tables.py) has blank space, filters defined on that
  table using FilterActions wont work.

Cause:
    -table name is used as the table id in the html
    -the table selector used in the quicksearch plugin has the
     following format:
	 table#<table id> tbody tr

     For example: if the table name specified in the Meta class of
     tables.py is 'foo bar', then the table selector will be:
         table#foo bar tbody tr.

Solution:
    Slugify the table name and use the slug name as the table id
    instead of original table name.

Change-Id: I9d7c0ea3519c8bebb2f1ac5831cb271557908ba9
Closes-Bug: 1311789

commit_message:
Allow retrying some failed requests

Connection Errors can be transient and there are many clients (including
auth_token middleware) that allow retrying requests that fail.

We should support this in the session, disabled by default, rather than
have multiple implementations for it.

For the moment I have purposefully not added it as an option to
Session.__init__ though I can see arguments for it. This can be added
later if there becomes a particular need.

I have also purposefully distinguished between Connection Errors (and
connect_retries) and HTTP errors. I don't know a good way to generalize
retrying on HTTP errors and they can be added later if required.

Blueprint: session-retries
Change-Id: Ia219636663980433ddb9c00c6df7c8477df4ef99

commit_message:
set max_length on volume/snapshot description text area

Currently, there is no max, but will close the modal and give
the generic "Unable to update volume." This is a preventable
error if we restrict to 255 chars to match Cinder.

Change-Id: I50e63929ed70dd7a899b7d157381d1f5ad2356cd
Closes-Bug: #1370186

commit_message:
Use Keystone client session.Session

This replaces the restapi requests wrapper with the one from Keystone client so
we can take advantage of the auth plugins.

As a first step only the v2 and v3 token and password plugins are supported.
This maintainis no changes to the command options or environment variables.

The next steps will include reworking the other API client interfaces to
fully utilize the single auth session.

Blueprint: ksc-session-auth
Change-Id: I47ec63291e4c3cf36c8061299a4764f60b36ab89

commit_message:
Console: warn that the Nova VMRC console driver will be deprecated in K

This code is not used and should be deprecated. In addition to this the
ESX driver was deprecated in commit 1deb31f85a8f5d1e261b2cf1eddc537a5da7f60b

Closes-bug: #1368202

Catch NotImplementedError on reset_network for xen

This patch adds a decorator around reset_network for
NotImplementedError.

This introduces a new extension for migrating a running instance
from nova-network to neutron.
Initially it migrates one instance at a time and accepts neutron
net_id as a parameter

TODO:
 - properly update instance info cache after successful migration
 - store the info (in info cache?) of which network api to use
for particular instance - neutron for migrated, nova-net for others
 - utilize nova instance lock mechanism

Remaining issues:
 - tested on the latest libvirt (1.2.5). Earlier versions may have
issues with network device update (not updating properly,
errors on clearing network filters)
 - dhcp may not work for newly created instances with nova-network
if neutron is running in parallel

Change-Id: I89db728a8a972b990c984fe3151bba2d6987f9de

commit_message:
WIP Neutron migration

This introduces a new extension for migrating a running instance
from nova-network to neutron.
Initially it migrates one instance at a time and accepts neutron
net_id as a parameter

Further steps:
 - handle security groups migration
 - handle floating_ips migration
 - create proper neutron network automatically depending on nova-net
network type
 - migrate a group of instances at a time (by tenant, network?)

Remaining issues:
 - tested on the latest libvirt versions (1.2.5). Earlier versions
may have issues with network device update (not updating properly,
errors on clearing network filters)

Implements blueprint neutron-migration

Change-Id: I89db728a8a972b990c984fe3151bba2d6987f9de

commit_message:
Bump FakeDriver's resource numbers

Bump the amount of memory and disk that FakeDriver reports so one can
schedule larger instances. One should be able to schedule an instance
larger with more then 8GB of ram onto the FakeDriver.

Since the FakeVirt driver is now used for much more then just unit
tests, subclass FakeVirt to decouple the amount of resources FakeVirt reports
from the amounts in the api_samples. This way the api_samples don't need changing every
time the resource amounts reported by FakeVirt are tweaked.

Change-Id: Ifd3b8bd1abf985d279de334776ed5feb4fa72a27
Related-Bug: #1268943

commit_message:
Sync oslo-incubator module log:

Pull in new default log level for stevedore.

Generated with: python update.py --base nova ../nova --modules log

Changes:
d9060f6 Check for namedtuple_as_object support before using it
ad248f6 Specify namedtuple_as_object=False when using simplejson
037dee0 Set stevedore log level to WARN by default

Change-Id: Ibe9d2e6e8d97e3199b18ef59c2346a7157574273
