commit_message:
Update Heat CLI test to pass with random hash

The failing test assumes ordering of the returned JSON
blob and asserts that the given server resource precedes
another resource.  This updates it and allows the test
to pass when the resource is listed at the end of the
section, which may happen depending on hash + dict
ordering.

Change-Id: I279a1a1f3081214b0a2b0f712d311d148acd7b8e

The files directory seems to be clashing with a files directory in the horizon elements
    http://logs.openstack.org/25/115525/3/check-tripleo/check-tripleo-novabm-overcloud-f20-nonha/790bb3e/console.html#_2014-08-20_10_58_27_050'}, {'account_id': 8688, 'date': '2014-08-20 12:05:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4: Code-Review+2

Derek, all elements get copied into one dir, so it's pretty unavoidable (and completely expected) to have the top-level element dirs share names. This is the same behaviour as seen by EG install.d/, os-apply-config/.

What would be bad is if two files in files/ share a name as then one would overwrite the other and get copied into 2+ places. To mitigate this, files in files/ should have a full path structure. This isn't a well-established mitigation but you can see Nick has done it in this review."}, {'account_id': 10373, 'date': '2014-08-20 12:05:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

commit_message:
Extract RabbitMQ config files from install.d to files/

Separate config files out of the install.d script into files/.
This is more readable.

Change-Id: I95da168ee56ef05ea7a75db2135bebd642b13588

commit_message:
Let zake act as a in-memory fully functional driver

The zake driver should theoretically function the same as the
non-local driver so all the same kazoo functions should work,
without the whole distributed part as they work with the regular
zookeeper backed kazoo driver.

Change-Id: I19df0da0e58c5624ca1b10f61c42510f1f104847

commit_message:
Don't expose X-Auth-Token in glance CLI

Glance CLI exposes X-Auth-Token in debug mode. This patch replaces
X-Auth-Token's value with '{SHA1}<sha1oftoken>'. Some credentials
are exposed by keystoneclient as glanceclient uses keystoneclient
to authenticate, it will be fixed in bug-100414.

Change-Id: Ia51c578d20a96aae143d86893a45134643bd4053
Closes-Bug: #1327019

commit_message:
Update ironic states and documentation

This adds doc strings for the various states, and updates the documentation
header to reflect the current state of states.

In addition, this removes the following unused states:
  - INIT
  - BUILDING
  - SUSPEND

commit_message:
Fix AuthPlugin authentification

AuthPlugin wrongly assumed that self.opts['token'] is always a function.

Change-Id: I968c62aec0d16d736693e403d03a495baf8ea15a
Closes-Bug: #1369461

commit_message:
Not permitted to delete pools which are used by flavor

Pool will be used when creating a flavor, in this case
use is not permitted to delete the pool except after
removing the relationship either by patching the flavor
to change the pool it used or deleting the flavor.

DocsImpact
Pool deletion can now fail with 403 if the pool is used by flavor

Change-Id: I8db78a0f55602a865f98eecb0035b139f1ab18b1
Closes-Bug: #1362174

commit_message:
Renaming 'stop_workflow' to 'pause_workflow'

* Renamed method 'stop_workflow' to 'pause_workflow' for engine
  and workflow handler.
* Renamed state 'STOPPED' to 'PAUSED' according to the name of
  engine instruction 'pause'

Change-Id: Iee549fe25e93d68a6c15b2ce2c5f2da0df9af080

commit_message:
Parametrize Swift partition power

The Swift partition power is currently hard-coded to 10.  While
this is fine for small Swift clusters there are some users who
will want to configure rings with higher partition powers.  We
have parametrized the value of the partition power, and the
default is set to 10.

Change-Id: If115cf5cf2f4c2ff7d28b0f5ae3d2ca3f4b4be5a

commit_message:
Only start zookeeper/memcached when not already running

Since openstack infra already runs these services (or will)
we should just use them when we can. Also for developers that
already have these services running we should use them when
we can instead of trying to recreate them.

Change-Id: I8655e5365ad36c57836f87e147102e2d02db7830

commit_message:
Fix volume name in 'test_volume_create' method

Default volume name was changed to 'ostf-test-volume'
by the commit # 00093c618ec2d013cfa964059c82c445cede068b
and this has led to permanently fail of OSTF check 'Create
volume and attach it to instance'.

Change-Id: Id9e514cc0b6ab60a4bbca33929f58afccf96bd4b
Closes-bug: #1369625

I'm OK with this from a fedora side.  Ken has tested on rhel6.

Not sure if there is precedent for adding a ppa on the ubuntu side.  Presumably this is temporary?"}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2014-08-25 12:29:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

In reading the blueprint the reason for the ppa is because of a desired gate job. However using ppa repos in the gate isn't an option due to reliability concerns, which is one of the reasons you don't see any ppa repos used in the rest of devstack.

I don't think we should be adding ppa to devstack as general policy. I also think that bubbling this up to generically devstack is probably the wrong option, and we should instead look at oslo messaging doing functional testing separately until such time as the distros actually have this kind of base software."}, {'account_id': 8770, 'date': '2014-08-25 13:51:21.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Hi Sean, thanks for the feedback.

I'll certainly pull the PPA.  While the required packages are not yet available via the proper ubuntu channels, they are available via EPEL, which - if I understand correctly - is enabled in devstack by default.  I'd be happy to rework the patch to remove the PPA and only support AMQP1.0 on epel-compatible distros until ubuntu support arrives.

However, the purpose of this change is greater than just satisfying the proposed gate check. I probably haven't done a good job of explaining the 'big picture'.  AMQP 1.0 is the primary focus of the Apache QPID team going forward.  This change, along with the new AMQP 1.0 oslo.messaging driver, is part of an effort to encourage QPID deployments towards this new protocol standard, and away from the deprecated 0-10 protocol.

So aside from the gate test, this change has value for those deployments that want to adopt the 1.0 protocol that is supported by the latest QPID broker."}, {'account_id': 7118, 'date': '2014-08-25 22:00:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Ken - there is no schism over support that would cause divergent implementations, right?  

Assuming everyone is working to the same goal, my feeling is that with full support on a range of platforms (basically all rpm based distros), then we shouldn't hold things up.  We can be doing real gate-testing of this feature on a f20 node

When ubuntu support is available, it should be in much better shape for the intervening testing that has been done"}, {'account_id': 8770, 'date': '2014-08-26 18:15:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2: Workflow-1

Sorry, folks - I forgot to take my Anti-Stupid pills this a.m.

I'm marking this patch a WIP for now.  I've hit a problem with this patch on Centos6.  While the AMQP 1.0 libraries are available on EPEL for Centos6, the version of qpidd is -way- old, and doesn't have AMQP 1.0 support :P

Centos7 and Fedora 20+ won't have this issue, as both use EPEL to get the latest libraries and qpidd."}, {'account_id': 7118, 'date': '2014-08-26 20:39:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I see that your gate test on fedora 20 [1] is using the functional tests under tox, i.e. this devstack change is not for use in the gate.

I think installing the ppa is helpful in getting the feature enabled, as long as Ken is willing to keep an eye on it and clean-up when appropriate.

My +2 is if [1] gets merged as a tox job, then I think this is OK for devstack 

[1] https://review.openstack.org/#/c/115752/'}, {'account_id': 2813, 'date': '2014-09-05 10:01:08.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 8770, 'date': '2014-09-10 15:13:57.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 8770, 'date': '2014-09-10 15:24:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1

Now that the AMQP 1.0 driver is in oslo.messenger, I've been able to test this change more thoroughly.

I've tested it on my Fedora 20 system, setting up a nova config.  Messaging appears ok - I can see rpc traffic on the qpid queues.

I've also removed support for those platforms that don't provide AMQP 1.0 support at the moment (ubuntu, centos6 specifically).  Attempting to enable AMQP 1.0 (default is disabled) on these platforms will cause devstack to exit with a descriptive error message. I'll open a tracking bug to re-enable support for these once AMQP 1.0 is available for them should this patch be accepted."}, {'account_id': 2813, 'date': '2014-09-10 15:55:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

@Ken: awesome, I wondering how to setup the --topic/queue-pattern, but your latest patchset do all of that automatically, thanks you :)'}, {'account_id': 2813, 'date': '2014-09-10 15:55:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-10 16:52:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

commit_message:
Add an option to enable version 1.0 of the AMQP messaging protocol

This change adds the RPC_MESSAGING_PROTOCOL configuration option that
selects the messaging protocol that is used by the RPC backend and
client.

Some brokers can support different kinds of 'on the wire' messaging
protocols.  Qpid, for example, supports both AMQP 0-10 (the default),
and AMQP 1.0.  Use the RPC_MESSAGING_PROTOCOL configuration variable
to override the default protocol for those brokers that support
multiple protocol options.

This new option is necessary in order to enable the new AMQP 1.0
oslo.messaging transport as described in the blueprint.

Note well: currently this AMQP 1.0 functionality is only available on
fedora 19+ platforms.  Support is WIP on ubuntu/debian and rhel/centos
7. Enabling the RPC_MESSAGING_PROTOCOL option on an unsupported
platform will cause devstack to exit with an approriate error
message.

Change-Id: Ib8dea59922844e87d6c947b5dca557f5b5fc1160
Implements: blueprint amqp10-driver-implementation

commit_message:
Redis driver does not failover to slave when master fails

 Add the ability to configure Sentinel support in zaqar.conf

 Read that config and use it to construct a Sentinel instance and discover
 the master in lieu of instantiating StrictRedis directly

 Test master-slave failover

 Partially-Implements: blueprint redis-storage-driver

Change-Id: I661269b2a04c6e48dcb1d76a0c21f17224e7b3a1

commit_message:
Clarifies local_settings file location

Clarifies local_settings file location according to Linux distribution, and makes a minor phrasing improvement in the Ryu plug-in section.

Change-Id: I19fca9541fd7556ed1cfb4682b1b9a38b72f073f
Closes-Bug: #1362860

Thank you for your first contribution to OpenStack.

    Your patch will now be tested automatically by OpenStack testing frameworks
    and once the automatic tests pass, it will be reviewed by other friendly
    developers. They will give you feedback and may require you to refine it.

    People seldom get their patch approved on the first try, so don't be
    concerned if requested to make corrections. Feel free to modify your patch
    and resubmit a new change-set.

    Patches usually take 3 to 7 days to be reviewed so be patient and be
    available on IRC to ask and answer questions about your work. The more you
    participate in the community the more rewarding it is for you. You may also
    notice that the more you get to know people and get to be known, the faster
    your patches will be reviewed and eventually approved. Get to know others
    and become known by doing code reviews: anybody can do it, and it's a
    great way to learn the code base.

    Thanks again for supporting OpenStack, we look forward to working with you.

    IRC: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/IRC
    Workflow: https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Gerrit_Workflow

commit_message:
Refactor oneline changelog walking.

We want to suck the changelog into the description as well, but we
don't want all of it there. Making it a generator of formatted
objects lets us apply some logic without conflating things or tying
it up too much. This patch does prep work for the long term goal.

Change-Id: Idd00c219891500210c83faeb0f2d4370add3b069

commit_message:
Allow DHCPv6 reply from server to client

Add security group rule to allow DHCPv6 reply from dhcp server
link local addres port 547 to client port 546.

Change-Id: I5fd9561e855b1d3999649934977af659d5ca221f

commit_message:
Add retry_on_deadlock to db update methods

There's some known races that have been addressed in
Nova via a retry_on_deadlock deocrator.  Some known
cases in Cinder exist as well when dealing with updates
to quotas and reservations_expire.

This patch introduces the decorator to Cinder and hits
the methods known to be susceptible to deadlock as well
as some others that seem as though they'd fall into the
same category.

Leverages work that's already been done in Nova

Co-Authored-By: Vish Ishaya <vishvananda@gmail.com>

Change-Id: Ic807f4f8a333e4d5477f86e41eea40191637087c
Partial-bug: #1350466
(cherry picked from commit 201adf31a57ea4d456ef5daf1eca2ed3b64fca85)

commit_message:
Add fix for reservation index to icehouse

Cinder doesn't have backportable migrations, so ensure the index
is added every time the migration runs.

DB migration in master that does the same thing was made in the
following commits:
  4d56b91628518629b47997b93acd9cb1e48f87f5
  08b90190085a11bc99112472944c193672061e1f
  479d6050f3f07e12488e6bb9a40b0aec3452a19c

Change-Id: I8bdab1a70f0076312aba4d0b6c4417b335947680
Resolves-bug: #1348720

[{'created': '2014-08-24 15:01:39.000000000', 'message': "Configuration token hashing algorithm

The user's authentication token was hashed using the MD5 algorithm.
The MD5 algorithm shouldn't be used because of the potential for
hash collisions. Some security standards mandate a SHA2 algorithm
or better must be used.

With this change the algorithm to use for hashing tokens can be
configured by setting the OPENSTACK_TOKEN_HASH_ALGORITHM
configuration option to a hash algorithm supported by Python's
hashlib library[1]. For example, a deployer could set the option to
'sha256' to meet a SHA2 security standard.

The algorithm chosen must match the hash algorithm that the
identity server is configured to use (Keystone and the auth_token
middleware can be configured to use any hash algorithm supported by
hashlib).

This is for security hardening.

commit_message:
Configurable token hashing algorithm

The user's authentication token was hashed using the MD5 algorithm.
The MD5 algorithm shouldn't be used because of the potential for
hash collisions. Some security standards mandate a SHA2 algorithm
or better must be used.

With this change the algorithm to use for hashing tokens can be
configured by setting the OPENSTACK_TOKEN_HASH_ALGORITHM
configuration option to a hash algorithm supported by Python's
hashlib library[1]. For example, a deployer could set the option to
'sha256' to meet a SHA2 security standard.

The algorithm chosen must match the hash algorithm that the
identity server is configured to use (Keystone and the auth_token
middleware can be configured to use any hash algorithm supported by
hashlib).

This is for security hardening.

[1] https://docs.python.org/2/library/hashlib.html

DocImpact
SecurityImpact

Change-Id: I9e3eba7e0a12ae40a08d0ed851ea916ec6591bcc
Closes-Bug: #1174499

commit_message:
Make test_shell independent of user's OS_REGION_NAME

test_shell was assuming that OS_REGION_NAME == '' and failed if
it was set differently - now test_shell specifies region name to
avoid such problems.

Change-Id: I307672b6819e1f611a6a1bfb3d2363b1d5c79298
Closes-Bug: #1367105

commit_message:
Isolate tests from HTTP_PROXY, OS_REGION_NAME env vars

CLI and shell tests call into a mock httpretty REST service.  If
HTTP_PROXY is set, urllib2/requests follows it and fails to hit the
mocked httpretty service as expected.

Also: The shell tests assumed OS_REGION_NAME was unset, so also clear
this.

Change-Id: I9a3f4981ee5c32203f9127e9eb8eefe5efd1b6dc
Closes-Bug: #1367102
Closes-Bug: #1367105

commit_message:
Barchart popup window position is broken

Barchart popup window position is broken with new styles,
need to compute it different way.
Also position while scaling was broken, fixing it too.

Closes-Bug: #1353918
Change-Id: I0151a0b93b8350e4ca3dbe429db66b6171b9d459

Fixup trove screens for Bootstrap 3 changes

Changed row-fluid
Selected new icons in a few places
Cleanup html for details pages
Added default button to resize dialog

Change-Id: I80fbccf77e6a27a51f84dd55cab7944f23d38d66

commit_message:
fix the logic of api.lbaas._pool_list

When the subnet is deleted first, _pool_list will access cidr from
a None object. As a result, a unexpected exception is thrown.

Change-Id: Iceb9dea1b0e8bab9ca54dfcdd2bf664c8677e0f2
Related-Bug: #1367615

commit_message:
Remove redundant waiter in create_volume cleanup

If wait_on_delete is True we are already waiting
for the volume delete, so the addCleanup_with_wait
call is redundant.

This just changes the addCleanup_with_wait call
to a normal addCleanup on the volume delete in
the case that wait_on_delete is True.

If wait_on_delete is False we still do the delete
but the wait is moved to the end of the test run
so it's asynchronous.

Change-Id: I6c4cd1a00ddc79de4c59c512b2d794e7380591f2
Partial-Bug: #1367857

commit_message:
Fix race condition in update_dhcp

This modifies linux_net to only make one query for the fixed ips.
Previously it was getting the list of fixed ips twice. It also
merges the convoluted logic around single_default_gateway into
the single query so that it doesn't make a db request per fixed ip.
This prevents a race condition that could lead to ips not allocating
properly if an instance is deleted while the dhcp config was being
updated. Also, e274c45dcd37f49d66cc3cce72c2fd97f444151c missed a
call to obj_make_compatible for instance version. This adds it
since it will be in a conflicting spot.

Change-Id: Iffdc60063b26c9e3f6b8dbe5b67301cbc19b2564
Resolves-bug: #1359510

Hi Zhenguo.

Thanks for the patch. It seems to me that the fix you provided is for a different bug. There are two issues I see around this use case:

1. Extending a volume to "beyond what the quota allows" does not check the requested size against the quota in place. This is what your patch fixes.

2. Extending a volume to "a size that is allowed by the quota but is beyond what is physically available" first shows a success message, then an "Error_Extending" message and the ongoing progress bar. This is the bug Cindy opened.

If this is the case, I suggest we file a bug for #1 above and associate this patch to that instead.'}, {'account_id': 9622, 'date': '2014-02-27 21:43:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: No score

Thanks for the patch Zhenguo. I'm afraid I don't think we should implement this in horizon. 

The reason is that the extend operation works based on reservations with refreshes and expirations periods. When you try to extend a volume, cinder actually tries to make a resource reservation and after that the driver do the extension itself. In this patch horizon is comparing the new size with the current usage which does not take reservations into account. So, simple example, let's say your project quota is 10GB, current usage is 8GB and you have reservations for 2GB. The validation will pass but the extend will fail. So this would introduce a non consistent user experience, sometimes horizon will tell you that you are over the project quota and sometimes it will fail with no reason"}, {'account_id': 6610, 'date': '2014-07-16 11:29:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

commit_message:
Add quota validation to volume extending size

We should validate extending size before handle the action
like create volume.

Change-Id: Ibc9f75d7b331e091af813a27ec5b0b68d7855e5d
Closes-Bug: #1285922

commit_message:
Don't delete stack domain project on stack-abandon

Currently we delete the stack domain project on abandon, which will
break any resources being abandoned that depend on users created in
the stack user domain.  So add a flag to skip deletion on abandon
and some tests to prove it works.

Change-Id: I883831a33d5bd326523836247683c161f797ee2a
Closes-Bug: #1300734

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-08-05 06:56:10.000000000', 'message': 'Fix summation code to handle invalid data

This patch fixes multiple test failures with Django 1.7 that
all ended with this:

"average": lambda data: sum(data, 0.0) / len(data)
TypeError: unsupported operand type(s) for +: 'float' and 'str'

With Django 1.6, the template code that looked up the variable behind
get_summation was catching the TypeError exception:

    try: # method call (assuming no args required)
        current = current()
    except TypeError: # arguments *were* required
        # GOTCHA: This will also catch any TypeError
        # raised in the function itself.
        current = settings.TEMPLATE_STRING_IF_INVALID  # invalid

With Django 1.7, the code has been refined to catch the exception only
when the function really requires argument (which get_summation()
doesn't):

    try:  # method call (assuming no args required)
        current = current()
    except TypeError:
        try:
            getcallargs(current)
        except TypeError:  # arguments *were* required
            current = settings.TEMPLATE_STRING_IF_INVALID  # invalid
        else:
            raise

So instead of blindly relying on sum(), I introduced a safe_sum() and
safe_average() functions which mimick the behaviour we got with Django
1.6 by returning an empty string when we have invalid input data.

Thanks to hertzog@debian.org for this patch.

Change-Id: I9d5b4565f1238a9880ccf117f2ea623fed466a44

commit_message:
Handle TypeError from table column summation code

This commit catches TypeError from horizon.tables.Column
summation calculation. This TypeError is caught inside Django
until Django 1.6, but Django 1.7 code is refined to catch
more specific case and it leads to horizon unit test failure.

Closes-Bug: #1355939
Change-Id: I9d5b4565f1238a9880ccf117f2ea623fed466a44

commit_message:
Fix alert styling using "error" instead of "danger".

There is no "alert-error" style, only "alert-danger" so rewrite the type
to "danger" for correct styling.

Change-Id: Ie812d5bbbbd84a1e9c6d94876c8726124d4fc4e9
Closes-Bug: 1362943

commit_message:
Cleanup trust on delete with stored context if needed

On delete, it's possible that someone other than the user who
created the stack may do the delete, e.g if there are a group
of heat users in a project who share responsibility for stacks.

Currently this causes an error if the user is not an admin,
because keystone default policy means only the trustor user (e.g
the user who originally delegated to heat via the trust on create)
or an admin may delete the trust.

So we check if the context user_id matches the user_creds trustor,
and if it doesn't we switch to the stored context to do the trust
cleanup so we avoid the delete failure.

I've avoided switching to the stored context unconditionally because
of the non-trivial overhead of creating a new keystoneclient object,
getting a new trust-scoped token etc.

Closes-Bug: #1308834
Change-Id: If408534ac7164e9d281dfbb6d4d39da97992f322

commit_message:
libvirt: avoid 30 second long test in LXC mount setup

The test_create_propagates_exceptions test case in the libvirt
driver test has a 30 second delay while disk setup times out.

  File "nova/virt/libvirt/driver.py", line 4412, in _create_domain_and_network
    disk_info):
  File "/usr/lib64/python2.7/contextlib.py", line 17, in __enter__
    return self.gen.next()
  File "nova/virt/libvirt/driver.py", line 4308, in _lxc_disk_handler
    self._create_domain_setup_lxc(instance, block_device_info, disk_info)
  File "nova/virt/libvirt/driver.py", line 4260, in _create_domain_setup_lxc
    use_cow=use_cow)
  File "nova/virt/disk/api.py", line 386, in setup_container
    dev = img.mount()
  File "nova/virt/disk/api.py", line 306, in mount
    if mounter.do_mount():
  File "nova/virt/disk/mount/api.py", line 218, in do_mount
    status = self.get_dev() and self.map_dev() and self.mnt_dev()
  File "nova/virt/disk/mount/nbd.py", line 120, in get_dev
    return self._get_dev_retry_helper()
  File "nova/virt/disk/mount/api.py", line 121, in _get_dev_retry_helper
    time.sleep(2)

Mock out the _create_domain_setup_lxc & _create_domain_cleanup_lxc
methods to avoid exercising this codepath which is irrelevant to the
goals of the test case.

Resolves-bug: #1369537
Change-Id: Ic860f83ac0b3b7242658640618b223d89c4db253

commit_message:
minimise ceilometer memory usage

according to memory_profiler, ceilometer collector and api uses
~40-45mb and ~66mb of memory respectively. importing the migration
module from oslo.db is ~5mb memory (8-15% of total memory usage).

this patch moves import so it imports the module only for migration
as it isn't needed for normal collector/api use.

Closes-Bug: #1369602
Change-Id: Ic5b116c88c40ea0b3a66694369cf6d76b9635c54

commit_message:
NSX: Correct allowed_address_pair return value on create_port

This patch fixes the NSX plugin to return [] rather than None for a
port does not have any allowed_address_pairs when a create_port api
call is made. Currently the NSX plugin is failing every patch because
now tempest is checking for this value to be [].

Change-Id: Ic82c564ff62000c367c544f44a76694be9375790
Closes-bug: 1366921
(cherry picked from commit 1361ad99969d2a729599720f06f8373db230e0ed)

[{'created': '2014-07-14 08:49:13.000000000', 'message': "Add affinity/anti-affinity filters

Cinder has done a good job hiding the details of storage backends from end
users by using volume types.  However there are use cases where users who
build their application on top of volumes would like to be able to 'choose'
where a volume be created on.  How can Cinder provide such capability without
hurting the simplicity we have been keeping?  Affinity/anti-affinity is one
of the flexibility we can provide without exposing details to backends.

The term affinity/anti-affinity here is to to describe the relationship
between two sets of volumes in terms of location.  To limit the scope, we
describe one volume is affinity with the other one only when they reside in
the same volume back-end (this notion can be extended to volume pools if
volume pool support lands in Cinder); on the contrary, 'anti-affinity'
relation between two sets of volumes simply implies they are on different
Cinder back-ends (pools).

This affinity/anti-affinity filter filters Cinder backend based on hint
specified by end user.  The hint expresses the affinity or anti-affinity
relation between new volumes and existing volume(s).  This allows end
users to provide hints like 'please put this volume to a place that is
different from where Volume-XYZ resides in'.

This change adds two new filters to Cinder - SameBackendFilter and
DifferentBackendFilter.  These two filters will look at the scheduler hint
provided by end users (via scheduler hint extension) and filter backends by
checking the 'host' of old and new volumes see if a backend meets the
requirement (being on the same backend as existing volume or not being on
the same backend(s) as existing volume(s)).

For example:
  Volume A is on 'backend 1', to create Volume B on the same backend as A,
  use:
    cinder create --hint same_host=VolA-UUID SIZE

  To create Volume C on different backend than that of A, use:
    cinder create --hint different_host=VolA-UUID SIZE

  Now, to create Volume D on different backend other than those of A and C,
  use:
    cinder create --hint different_host=VolA-UUID --hint
    different_host=VolC-UUID SIZE

implements bp: affinity-antiaffinity-filter

DocImpact

Change-Id: I19f298bd87b0069c0d1bb133202188d3bf65b770

commit_message:
Add affinity/anti-affinity filters

Cinder has done a good job hiding the details of storage backends from end
users by using volume types.  However there are use cases where users who
build their application on top of volumes would like to be able to 'choose'
where a volume be created on.  How can Cinder provide such capability without
hurting the simplicity we have been keeping?  Affinity/anti-affinity is one
of the flexibility we can provide without exposing details to backends.

The term affinity/anti-affinity here is to to describe the relationship
between two sets of volumes in terms of location.  To limit the scope, we
describe one volume is affinity with the other one only when they reside in
the same volume back-end (this notion can be extended to volume pools if
volume pool support lands in Cinder); on the contrary, 'anti-affinity'
relation between two sets of volumes simply implies they are on different
Cinder back-ends (pools).

This affinity/anti-affinity filter filters Cinder backend based on hint
specified by end user.  The hint expresses the affinity or anti-affinity
relation between new volumes and existing volume(s).  This allows end
users to provide hints like 'please put this volume to a place that is
different from where Volume-XYZ resides in'.

This change adds two new filters to Cinder - SameBackendFilter and
DifferentBackendFilter.  These two filters will look at the scheduler hint
provided by end users (via scheduler hint extension) and filter backends by
checking the 'host' of old and new volumes see if a backend meets the
requirement (being on the same backend as existing volume or not being on
the same backend(s) as existing volume(s)).

For example:
  Volume A is on 'backend 1', to create Volume B on the same backend as A,
  use:
    cinder create --hint same_host=VolA-UUID SIZE

  To create Volume C on different backend than that of A, use:
    cinder create --hint different_host=VolA-UUID SIZE

  Now, to create Volume D on different backend other than those of A and C,
  use:
    cinder create --hint different_host=VolA-UUID --hint
    different_host=VolC-UUID SIZE
  or:
    cinder create --hint different_host="[VolA-UUID, VolC-UUID]" SIZE

implements bp: affinity-antiaffinity-filter

DocImpact

Change-Id: I19f298bd87b0069c0d1bb133202188d3bf65b770

When creating the dummy trust context, we return an arbitrary
hard-coded trustor_user_id, which makes testing we do things
with the trustor correctly difficult, so instead return the
user_id passed into the client (as this is what the trustor id

commit_message:
Tests update FakeKeystoneClient to align user_id and trustor

When creating the dummy trust context, we return an arbitrary
hard-coded trustor_user_id, which makes testing we do things
with the trustor correctly difficult, so instead return the
user_id passed into the client (as this is what the trustor id
will be when real create_trust_context calls happen)

Change-Id: I280b820977bfc533126fe392e002210a996311f0

commit_message:
Move javelin2 over to use oslo logging

javelin2 uses the tempest openstack clients which use oslo
logging, so make the logs generated directly by javelin2 and not the
tempest clients use oslo logging as well.

This way don't have to configure logging twice and can keep all javelin2
logs in the same place (as controlled by tempest.conf)

Change-Id: I09b5a13e9cd1511279163e07f780438c478d7af3

commit_message:
Compute v2 api server status value cleanup

Server status need to be updated to reflect current standards.
Adding statuses like STOPPED, PAUSED, SOFT_DELETED and updating
old values to new ones like RESCUED, RESIZED, DELETED.

Change-Id: I0926e2d1f51f8a8b5665cc8782ed421f8d56a4d7
Closes-Bug: #1362845

commit_message:
Stop using intersphinx

Remove intersphinx from the docs build as it triggers network calls that
occasionally fail, and we don't really use intersphinx (links other
sphinx documents out on the internet)

This also removes the requirement for internet access during docs build.

This causes docs jobs to fail because we error out on warnings.

Change-Id: I71e941e2a639641a662a163c682eb86d51de42fb
Related-Bug: #1368910

I updated glance content in the installation guide for Juno
as follows:

1) Removed prompts specific to MySQL because most distributions
   will use MariaDB.
2) Explicitly created endpoint with 'regionOne' region to avoid
   inconsistent defaults.
3) Recommended enabling verbose logging.
4) Replace 'auth_*' keys with 'identity_uri' key.
5) Added example command output.
6) Changed CirrOS version to 0.3.3 which affects several other
   files.

Change-Id: Id12735744bc44d884e4519d17cc317b703e3ab85
"}]
commit_message:
Update glance content for Juno

I updated glance content in the installation guide for Juno
as follows:

1) Removed prompts specific to MySQL because most distributions
   will use MariaDB.
2) Explicitly created endpoint with 'regionOne' region to avoid
   inconsistent defaults.
3) Recommended enabling verbose logging.
4) Replace 'auth_*' keys with 'identity_uri' key.
5) Added example command output.
6) Changed CirrOS version to 0.3.3 which affects several other
   files.

Change-Id: Id12735744bc44d884e4519d17cc317b703e3ab85

commit_message:
Use renamed _fail_second_call() in cisco nexus tests

In commit 5e4b0c6fc6670ea036d801ce53444272bc311929 NeutronDbPluginV2TestCase
_do_side_effect() was renamed to _fail_second_call(), but the nexus test cases
were not updated. The tests still worked because they check for
HTTPInternalServerError which is the end result of the server encountering
"AttributeError: object has no attribute '_do_side_effect'". So the fault
injection still worked, but not in the way intended.

Note: the monolithic nexus plugin is not updated here since it is being
removed from the tree.

Closes-bug: #1367552

Change-Id: I083285fff5144d8dc35bd5b64faa7e400c68bcff

commit_message:
Fix Invalid pathname for netapp cmode driver

In different Data ONTAP API versions exists incompatibility using
'nfs-exportfs-append-rules-2' API call.
8.2 requires field 'pathname' equal to volume's 'junction_path',
but 8.2.1 requires 'pathname' with prefix '/vol/' to volume's 'junction_path'.
So, make workaround for backend API trying second variant if first failed.

Change-Id: I63b70a3fe0895a1306c2b2c60d706965b141a184
Closes-Bug: #1365151

commit_message:
Clear the created server in FloatingIPsTestJSON's tearDown method.

The test case:
api/compute/floating_ips/test_floating_ips_actions.py:FloatingIPsTestJSON
does create a server in it's setUp, for doing floating ip test, but in it's
tearDown method, it does not clear the created server.

This left instance will interfere other testcases, and maybe make them fail.

Closes-Bug: #1369434

Change-Id: Iad69d8b10932f8c7ee3563c6b38d34121c6965a3

commit_message:
ironic client to use os_region_name if provided

Currently ironicclient does not pass OS_REGION_NAME to Keystone client.
That will cause problems in multiregion deployments.

Modified ironicclient to consider using OS_REGION_NAME if provided.

Closes-Bug: #1314159

Change-Id: I885e57973ccec64471fe2ba5fecfab2224829787

[{'created': '2014-09-13 07:25:39.000000000', 'message': "Stop using intersphinx

Remove intersphinx from the docs build as it triggers network calls that
occasionally fail, and we don't really use intersphinx (links other
sphinx documents out on the internet)

This also removes the requirement for internet access during docs build.

This can cause docs jobs to fail if the project errors out on
warnings.

Change-Id: I71e941e2a639641a662a163c682eb86d51de42fb
Related-Bug: #1368910
"}]
commit_message:
Stop using intersphinx

Remove intersphinx from the docs build as it triggers network calls that
occasionally fail, and we don't really use intersphinx (links other
sphinx documents out on the internet)

This also removes the requirement for internet access during docs build.

This can cause docs jobs to fail if the project errors out on
warnings.

Change-Id: I71e941e2a639641a662a163c682eb86d51de42fb
Related-Bug: #1368910

commit_message:
Don't display duplicated security groups

As reported by users, we end up displaying duplicate security groups
on multi nic vms using neutron. Let's not do that.

Also add security group listing to the v3 client to make it
consistent.

Change-Id: I0a983aac08aaeacf3c2aef5aae49f64265fe78c5
Closes-Bug: #1331307

commit_message:
Update keystone content for Juno

I updated keystone content in the installation guide for Juno
as follows:

1) Added step to manually create '_member_' role because
   source/package no longer creates it automatically.
2) Removed defunct 'log_dir' workaround for Ubuntu.
3) Explicitly created endpoint with 'regionOne' region to avoid
   inconsistent defaults.
4) Recommended enabling verbose logging.
5) Removed prompts specific to MySQL because most distributions
   will use MariaDB.
6) Improved consistency with similar content from other services
   as approved with the installation guide improvements project.

Change-Id: I46a95f9a29bfab4da9961d2393f33ff65c46aec4

commit_message:
Clear the created server in FloatingIPsTestJSON's tearDown method.

The test case:
api/compute/floating_ips/test_floating_ips_actions.py:FloatingIPsTestJSON
does create a server in it's setUp, for doing floating ip test, but in it's
tearDown method, it does not clear the created server.

This left instance will interfere other testcases, and maybe make them fail.

Closes-Bug: #1369434
Change-Id: I2e7bc02e9ad6ec9cf19bd86680caa7ef8731d0a1

commit_message:
Hash X-Auth-Token in neutron client log

Problem:
neutronclient is logging the X-Auth-Token in the nova logs.
Since the logs are world-readable, this means anyone user on
this system can see the auth token, which they can then use
to get OpenStack administrator access.

This fix solves this problem by hashing X-Auth-Token in
request headers in logs.

The password in request body and auth token in response
body will be hanlded in another commit which use keystone
client to authenticate.

Change-Id: Ibda3c1069a5a2d7af27bf95c7cef97bc103b5cde
Closes-Bug: 1320098

commit_message:
Remove exclude coverage regex from coverage job

This commit removes the regex to exclude the coverage extension from
the tox coverage job. The regex was needed for the unit tests on the
coverage extension, (which would mock out coverage) however that
extension has since been removed from nova. So we no longer need to
exclude tests that don't exist anymore.

Change-Id: I45685b1113ecc78eda92f13755ff2274ff517829

commit_message:
libvirt: improve unit test time

There were unit tests that were taking more than 4 seconds.

nova.tests.virt.libvirt.test_driver.LibvirtConnTestCase.test_clean_shutdown_failure    5.091
nova.tests.virt.libvirt.test_driver.LibvirtConnTestCase.test_clean_shutdown_with_retry 4.093

TrivialFix

Change-Id: I75cdb74dca69a1e31d6b974148c9590328c362e1
Closes-bug: #1366549

commit_message:
Cleanup floatingips also on router delete

In router remove path process_router(), processing of floating ips
is getting skipped. This change adds processing of floating ips
if the external gateway for the router was previously set. Since
DVR uses FIP namespaces and agent gateway ports, this change ensures
such ports and namespaces are removed.

Change-Id: Ib1d8fb54adcd8aab411dced695d171376687c980
Partial-bug: #1367588

commit_message:
Make sure libvirt VIR_ERR_NO_DOMAIN errors are handled correctly

Some libvirt VIR_ERR_NO_DOMAIN errors leak outside of the libvirt
driver, which may result in instances being set to ERROR state.

Make sure such errors are either ignored (during destroy) or
otherwise turned into InstanceNotFound errors.

Change-Id: I0ac2989062247a05162825760367488f4f90bd04
Closes-Bug: #1368404

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-07-30 11:35:23.000000000', 'message': 'Enable host aggregate metadata update

Nova currently expose an api to let the users update
the host aggregates metadata so horizon should expose
this functionality. At the same time Glance is exposing
a metadata dictionary in Juno, where users can register
the key/value pairs that describe their cloud deployment

This patch uses the glance metadata api to expose the available
metadata and the nova api to update the aggregates metadata

Change-Id: I4abf88426f548c47a21920169f710d3310e3ede6
Implements: blueprint host-aggregate-update-metadata

commit_message:
Enable host aggregate metadata update

Nova currently expose an api to let the users update
the host aggregates metadata so horizon should expose
this functionality. At the same time Glance is exposing
a metadata dictionary in Juno, where users can register
the key/value pairs that describe their cloud deployment.

This patch uses the glance metadata api to expose the available
metadata and the nova api to update the aggregates metadata

Co-Authored-By: Santiago Baldassin <santiago.b.baldassin@intel.com>
Co-Authored-By: Pawel Skowron <pawel.skowron@intel.com>
Co-Authored-By: Bartosz Fic <bartosz.fic@intel.com>
Co-Authored-By: Michal Dulko <michal.dulko@intel.com>
Co-Authored-By: Pawel Koniszewski <pawel.koniszewski@intel.com>
DocImpact
Change-Id: I4abf88426f548c47a21920169f710d3310e3ede6
Implements: blueprint host-aggregate-update-metadata

Hi Gloria!

The glance client that supports this feature has been stuck in unrelated elastic recheck bugs on Zuul for a couple days. It is a high priority thing for glance and should have merged, but the random failures and extraordinary queue times on zuul that are unrelated to it have been keeping it from merging for a couple days.  So until it finally goes through, there is a script you can use to get those patches onto your system.  I'm copying it below, but please note that this is a point in time script and we'll update the real script at the bottom of the following URL:

https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/j3-glance-patches

#!/bin/bash
 
cd /opt/stack
cd glance
git reset --hard HEAD
git checkout master
git review -x 111483 #Seed
glance-manage db_load_metadefs /opt/stack/glance/etc/metadefs
cd ../python-glanceclient
git reset --hard HEAD
git checkout master
git review -x 105231
cd ../horizon
git reset --hard HEAD
git checkout master
git pull --ff-only origin master
git review -x 104956 # Base widget + images
git review -x 110612 # Host Aggregates
git review -x 112874 # Flavors
git review -x 104063 # Namespace admin
sudo service apache2 restart
sudo python setup.py install
echo
echo Please Manually restart Glance API Service"}, {'account_id': 7665, 'date': '2014-09-04 17:15:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 22:

BTW, Gloria, this script does do git reset, so please take care to not have outstanding changes.'}, {'account_id': 11880, 'date': '2014-09-04 18:55:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 22:

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-08-08 13:56:39.000000000', 'message': 'Enable flavors metadata update

Nova currently expose an api to let the users update
the flavors metadata so horizon should expose
this functionality. At the same time Glance is exposing
a metadata dictionary in Juno, where users can register
the key/value pairs that describe their cloud deployment.
This patch uses the glance metadata api to expose the available
metadata and the nova api to update the aggregates metadata.

Change-Id: Ica9d3d06314a4d5afa77f644bd1f8900a1c328f7
Implements: blueprint glaance-metadata-flavors

commit_message:
Enable flavors metadata update

Nova currently expose an api to let the users update
the flavors metadata so horizon should expose
this functionality. At the same time Glance is exposing
a metadata dictionary in Juno, where users can register
the key/value pairs that describe their cloud deployment.
This patch uses the glance metadata api to expose the available
metadata and the nova api to update the aggregates metadata.

Implements: blueprint glaance-metadata-flavors

Co-Authored-By: Santiago Baldassin <santiago.b.baldassin@intel.com>
Co-Authored-By: Pawel Skowron <pawel.skowron@intel.com>
Co-Authored-By: Pawel Koniszewski <pawel.koniszewski@intel.com>
Co-Authored-By: Michal Dulko <michal.dulko@intel.com>

DocImpact:
    New UI. FLAVOR_EXTRA_KEYS setting deprecated.

Change-Id: Ica9d3d06314a4d5afa77f644bd1f8900a1c328f7

commit_message:
Add SELinux policy for Horizon

httpd, due to Horizon,  needs SELinux policy to allow it to connect to
the various ports for the OpenStack services. We can add this policy by
setting the SELinux boolean httpd_can_network_connect.

Change-Id: I663e543ddb1738c5e2de40b37d5a0e697762feb4
Closes-Bug: 1361630

commit b31fc6da27f49fa32e330af5d8342bf700e99620

commit 25cbcf5c8ab68c2805d6cf4f2ddaa77ac0f2ca22
Author: Nathan Kinder <nkinder@redhat.com>
Date:   Fri Sep 5 07:25:21 2014 -0700

    Avoid conversion of binary LDAP values

    A few of the LDAP searches performed in the identity and assignment
    LDAP drivers do not specify the list of attributes to return, which
    causes all attributes present in the LDAP entry to be returned.  We
    attempt to convery these values from utf8 to unicode, which fails
    when we encounter a binary value.  This patch addresses this problem
    in two ways.

    The first is to only request the attributes that we actually need
    returned from the LDAP server.  This avoids potential binary values
    that we do not even need to be concerned with.

    The second thing this patch does is to make our conversion code
    more tolerant by ignoring attributes that contain binary values.  If
    a binary value is present, we simply skip over that attribute in
    the conversion and log a debug message.  We should not be encounting
    binary values in a typical Keystone deployment, but this gives us
    some protection just in case we do encounter a binary value.

    Conflicts:
            keystone/assignment/backends/ldap.py
            keystone/identity/backends/ldap.py

    Closes-bug: #1355489
    Change-Id: I62325ab9c75bac67cca329fb7bd3c74aea7d2867
    (cherry picked from commit 940551c6bdd1477574c1dee165efe75366343bd7)

commit c48ec389fd2e4efc5e35b16735bf5a250db6b0cf
Author: Juan Antonio Osorio <juan.osorio.robles@ericsson.com>

    No longer allow listing users by email

    As specified in the bug description, the listing of users by using the
    email attribute as a filter would cause an exception. This is because
    the email is not a first class attribute, yet it was considered so in
    the filters. Thus, this fix will prevent the exception while also
    preventing the filtering by email.

commit c6cd627ea09e7d0dc40eee58ab2784353a71b2e0
Author: Nathan Kinder <nkinder@redhat.com>
Date:   Sat Jun 28 08:05:42 2014 -0700

    Implicitly ignore attributes that are mapped to None in LDAP

    Attributes that are mapped to None in LDAP trigger a 500 error when
    performing a search if they are not explicitly ignored in keystone's
    configuration.  These attributes should always be ignored, even if
    the admin left the attribute out of the ignore list.

    Change-Id: Ibbabdd0013059d5720250816764021a0b3ce8ce0
    Closes-bug: #1335437
    (cherry picked from commit 10a3edb7800d380ed72fcbbaae98251998c0e2c7)

Author: Chuck Short <chuck.short@canonical.com>

    Change-Id: I0015685b92ba405307240f163ecb43b7080ca6dd

commit 6cbf835542d62e6e5db4b4aef7141b1731cad9dc
Author: Brant Knudson <bknudson@us.ibm.com>
Date:   Thu Jul 31 17:47:00 2014 -0500

    Fix revocation event handling with MySQL

    When MySQL is used to store revocation events, events are returned
    from the database with the timestamps truncated to the second. This
    causes a revocation event for a token (which has the issued_at
    timestamp to the microsecond) to not match the revocation event and
    therefore the token is not considered to be revoked.

    The fix is to have the revocation events and token timestamps both
    always be truncated to the second. This will cause all tokens for a
    user that are issued within a second to be revoked when any of those
    tokens are revoked, which shouldn't be a problem.

    Conflicts:

    	keystone/tests/test_v3_os_revoke.py

    Change-Id: Ibd82b4ce910206dfd504c396614ae2ebed025e9b
    Closes-Bug: #1347961
    (cherry picked from commit 7aee6304f653475a4130dc3e5be602e91481f108)

commit c900a6ef25f213807d964c86682b3d35b74c7d2d
Author: Adam Young <ayoung@redhat.com>
Date:   Thu Apr 24 16:15:06 2014 -0400

    Make test_revoke expiry times distinct

    Calling _future_time had the possibility of returning the same value
    if it is called between clock ticks.  It appears to be happening in
    gate, potentially due to being run in a VM.

    Do not log 14+ INFO lines on a broken pipe error (eventlet)

    Under eventlet if the client disconnects while Keystone is trying
    to transmit data, approximately 14 lines of traceback are logged.

    This could result in massive logs if done repeatedly; worst case
    scenario could include a denial of service due to disk space being
    exhausted.

    Closes-Bug: #1334466

commit 25cbcf5c8ab68c2805d6cf4f2ddaa77ac0f2ca22
Author: Nathan Kinder <nkinder@redhat.com>
Date:   Fri Sep 5 07:25:21 2014 -0700

    Avoid conversion of binary LDAP values

    A few of the LDAP searches performed in the identity and assignment
    LDAP drivers do not specify the list of attributes to return, which
    causes all attributes present in the LDAP entry to be returned.  We
    attempt to convery these values from utf8 to unicode, which fails
    when we encounter a binary value.  This patch addresses this problem
    in two ways.

    The first is to only request the attributes that we actually need
    returned from the LDAP server.  This avoids potential binary values
    that we do not even need to be concerned with.

    The second thing this patch does is to make our conversion code
    more tolerant by ignoring attributes that contain binary values.  If
    a binary value is present, we simply skip over that attribute in
    the conversion and log a debug message.  We should not be encounting
    binary values in a typical Keystone deployment, but this gives us
    some protection just in case we do encounter a binary value.

    Conflicts:
            keystone/assignment/backends/ldap.py
            keystone/identity/backends/ldap.py

    Closes-bug: #1355489
    Change-Id: I62325ab9c75bac67cca329fb7bd3c74aea7d2867
    (cherry picked from commit 940551c6bdd1477574c1dee165efe75366343bd7)

    the admin left the attribute out of the ignore list.

commit 6cbf835542d62e6e5db4b4aef7141b1731cad9dc
Author: Brant Knudson <bknudson@us.ibm.com>
Date:   Thu Jul 31 17:47:00 2014 -0500

    Fix revocation event handling with MySQL

    When MySQL is used to store revocation events, events are returned
    from the database with the timestamps truncated to the second. This
    causes a revocation event for a token (which has the issued_at
    timestamp to the microsecond) to not match the revocation event and
    therefore the token is not considered to be revoked.

    The fix is to have the revocation events and token timestamps both
    always be truncated to the second. This will cause all tokens for a
    user that are issued within a second to be revoked when any of those
    tokens are revoked, which shouldn't be a problem.

    Conflicts:

    	keystone/tests/test_v3_os_revoke.py

    Change-Id: Ibd82b4ce910206dfd504c396614ae2ebed025e9b
    Closes-Bug: #1347961
    (cherry picked from commit 7aee6304f653475a4130dc3e5be602e91481f108)

commit c900a6ef25f213807d964c86682b3d35b74c7d2d
Author: Adam Young <ayoung@redhat.com>
Date:   Thu Apr 24 16:15:06 2014 -0400

    Make test_revoke expiry times distinct

    Calling _future_time had the possibility of returning the same value
    if it is called between clock ticks.  It appears to be happening in
    gate, potentially due to being run in a VM.

    Instead, for the loop that revokes distinct events,
    Assign each a different expires_at time.

    Conflicts:

    	keystone/tests/test_revoke.py

    Change-Id: Iab7ed92bb1e142651265a167ae73d6d1225b01a9
    Closes-Bug: #1300581

    The region table was not specified as being InnoDB or UTF8 under
    mysql initially. The migration will fail if the defaults for MySQL
    are not set correctly. A new method has been added to the
    migration_helpers module to detect and correct the InnoDB / UTF8
    specific issue with the region table.

    Change-Id: I374c3dd46a4292e8f9e74ef75a8bb463b951f135
    Closes-Bug: #1334779

commit 1a321f0b682661cab062f2c551bc3807fa043d8b
Author: OpenStack Proposal Bot <openstack-infra@lists.openstack.org>
Date:   Tue Jul 1 18:47:42 2014 +0000

    Updated from global requirements

    Change-Id: I8402f264446d94c43d00ef56fd0eb43a1551d979

commit 2baae7855bea0e151931c15b161a4b0742650c14
Author: Morgan Fainberg <morgan.fainberg@gmail.com>
Date:   Wed Jun 25 17:45:24 2014 -0700

    Do not log 14+ INFO lines on a broken pipe error (eventlet)

    Under eventlet if the client disconnects while Keystone is trying
    to transmit data, approximately 14 lines of traceback are logged.

    This could result in massive logs if done repeatedly; worst case
    scenario could include a denial of service due to disk space being
    exhausted.

    Change-Id: Iaf14c64799daa7539d1bd85cb6c6457380c111d9
    Closes-Bug: #1334466

Change-Id: I5faa0ba4882a8a994884bf51880df8c9edccb0c5

commit_message:
Fix topology page issue with deps and images

Topology page now shows dependencies between apps or networks
Add app images to topology page
Show real app images instead of dummy app icon.

Change-Id: Ia8c1588239a4d6ea185866f0dd536f2c18178761
Closes-Bug: #1336587

When using the yum element, we should reset the changes we've made to
/etc/yum.conf during post-install.d. Otherwise, this build time
configuration is propagated into booted instances.

Change-Id: I1eea586ca0fefe9bc0cf91fedefcbd141a536fa2

commit_message:
Reset yum configuration in post-install.d

When using the yum element, we should reset the changes we've made to
/etc/yum.conf during post-install.d. Otherwise, this build time
configuration is propagated into booted instances.

I think that the scope of this note needs to change.  There are a few problems with the recommendation to find and kill connections that are made over the floating IP address:

- We don't know what OS an instance might be running and what tools are available.

- Assuming that the instance was running Linux, the conntrack kernel module might very likely not be loaded (it wasn't on the Fedora 20 cloud image that I checked).  Even after loading the kernel module, the /proc/net/ip_conntrack file is not created.  I had to install the conntrack-tools package to make the 'conntrack' command available.

- Conntrack doesn't even know about the NAT that's used for floating IPs, as it's being handled by Neutron and not the instance itself.  I verified this by running the 'conntrack' command with active ssh connections coming in over both the private IP and the floating IP.  All incoming connections have the destination field (dst) as the private IP even when connections are made against the floating IP.

- Neutron should have information on the connections, but that doesn't help users who are disassociating floating IPs from instances.

I think that the only thing we can really recommend is that instances be terminated or stopped when disassociating floating IP addresses to ensure that all connections are closed."}, {'account_id': 10281, 'date': '2014-09-10 19:26:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

commit_message:
Add verification support to the agent

Allows Ironic to verify a node's hardware matches what an operator
entered when creating the node/port objects. This is useful for ensuring
node.properties is correct when switching workloads. For example, Ironic
can ensure that the amount of memory didn't change (possibly due to a
failed stick of RAM) since the last verification. Ironic could then
put the node in maintenance until an admin either changes node.properties
or replaces the defective part, and then sets the node's maintenance flag
to false. It can also be used to ensure the ports are plugged in correctly
(in a custom hardware manager), to avoid needless Neutron errors.

Change-Id: I1cd8f6476a9d2643a8e27745eb96e804564001ee

[{'created': '2014-09-08 21:06:07.000000000', 'message': 'Fixed bug in materializedViewTheory

One of the recently reactivated tests was broken,
probably because of some code cleanup done when
the tests were deactivated.  The bug arises with
how the materializedViewTheory handles the insertion
or deletion of rules when data is already present.
The bug arose because we were trying to compute
the new data that should be added/deleted when
inserting/deleting a rule at the time that
rule was enqueued to the processing queue.

This change fixes that bug by moving
the computation of new data from the enqueueing
step to the processing step.  It also reactivates
the test that was broken.

Change-Id: I690d48c4e1f99a214d7000741e7476ada90d9e3e

commit_message:
Fixed bug in materializedViewTheory

One of the recently reactivated tests was broken,
probably because of some code cleanup done when
the tests were deactivated.  The bug arises with
how the materializedViewTheory handles the insertion
or deletion of rules when data is already present.
The bug arose because we were trying to compute
the new data that should be added/deleted when
inserting/deleting a rule at the time that
rule was enqueued to the processing queue.

This change fixes that bug by moving
the computation of new data from the enqueueing
step to the processing step.  It also reactivates
the test that was broken.

Change-Id: I690d48c4e1f99a214d7000741e7476ada90d9e3e

commit_message:
Add version /v1 to url in congress api

This patch just adds /v1/ to each api method so we can have a versioned
api url and updates the docs.

Change-Id: Iea633f2c0ae22a575fcc8f581409923b713468d9
Closes-bug: 1343542

commit_message:
Client modifications to support versioned api

This patch adds the version number to the url. This will need to
land after the congress-server change goes in that adds the version
to the server as well.

commit_message:
Cells: Update set_admin_password for objects

Cells code was calling the compute/api set_admin_password method with an
old-world style instance and failing on the task_state attribute access.
This adds set_admin_password to the list of methods handled via the
cells RPC redirect method which is objects compatible.

Change-Id: I12e212260ed62dc9380202de31fda928a9498dcb
Closes-Bug: #1335315

commit_message:
Don't swallow exceptions in deallocate_port_for_instance

This uses the new _delete_ports method to (1) still
ignore 404 errors but also (2) raise up non-404 errors
from the neutron client when deleting the port fails as
we shouldn't be masking over this since the nova-api
call wouldn't be failing even though the underlying
operation failed.

Change-Id: Id05ea47ba03e0b60ae3a296920159e8189f9dd55
Related-Bug: #1292243

commit_message:
Improve secgroup create error message

Fixes secgroup create API so that when it is passed a name
or description field which is an empty string the error message
specifies which field is of the incorrect format.

Change-Id: Ieff67438965a735f2328390125bb4e66aec5e83d
Closes-Bug: 1369358

Remove intersphinx from the docs build as it triggers network calls that
occasionally fail, and we don't really use intersphinx (links other
sphinx documents out on the internet)

This also removes the requirement for internet access during docs build.

This can cause docs jobs to fail if the project errors out on

Related-Bug: #1368910

commit_message:
Stop using intersphinx

Remove intersphinx from the docs build as it triggers network calls that
occasionally fail, and we don't really use intersphinx (links other
sphinx documents out on the internet)

This also removes the requirement for internet access during docs build.

This can cause docs jobs to fail if the project errors out on
warnings.

Change-Id: I71e941e2a639641a662a163c682eb86d51de42fb
Related-Bug: #1368910

commit_message:
Fix NoSuchOptError on Couchbase create

A previous commit moved the backup_incremental_strategy option from
DEFAULT group to datastore specific grouping. However, the option was
only implemented for Mysql and Percona so when any datastore that had
backup support (like Couchbase) attempted to start, it received a
NoSuchOptError because of the missing option.

This fix put an empty dict in for the option for all datastores that
don't currently have backup or incremental backup support implemented.

Note: this wasn't picked up by any automated tests because the gate
currently only tests MySQL.

Author: Doug Shelley <doug@parelastic.com>
Co-Authored-By: Amrith Kumar <amrith@tesora.com>
Change-Id: I6a11dcf79c483a43ebdf79085d1bd17d653afe59
Closes-Bug: 1366175

Build succeeded.

- gate-heat-specs-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/04/115804/1/check/gate-heat-specs-docs/cd89621/doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 1m 24s'}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2014-08-21 14:37:33.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

(3 comments)

I don't really want to turn Heat into a template translation service, and I don't really understand why anyone would.

I would like to fix the API to look more native, but given that we have to keep the current format anyway to avoid breaking existing clients, it seems better to just wait and do it more tidily in the v2 API."}, {'account_id': 9189, 'date': '2014-08-21 20:13:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

(3 comments)

Whether we do it now or in V2, I think it's important to name our calls properly.

I would think that either we don't bother translating a template into any format, or we should at least translate it to what's supported.

"/validate" returning some fixed format that's not even compatible with any template format we already have seems wrong to me.'}, {'account_id': 7256, 'date': '2014-08-28 20:37:34.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

I agree with Anderson. This call, whatever its original intent, was always poorly named at best. IMO, if a UI needs some sort of "standard parameter format" to make its life easier, I think that's on the UI, not the orchestration service. Having a call to pre-validate a template, however, seems reasonable without all the conversion/response hooey.'}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2014-08-28 22:25:12.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

(3 comments)

We all agree that the current API is rubbish, it's a question of what we can _usefully_ do to change it now without breaking backwards compatibility."}, {'account_id': 9189, 'date': '2014-09-15 21:47:49.000000000', 'content': 'Abandoned'}]

commit_message:
Improve the behavior of /validate

/validate should at least allow you to select the output of the template
at the end or be refactored into two separate calls.

Implements: blueprint improve-template-validate
Change-Id: I64debfa457621e4be83740cc24a89a4607bf8aba

commit_message:
Run environment.d hook for manifests earlier

15-pip-manifests depends on the variables defined by the manifests
element, so we need to run this one earlier. I would have thought things
were alpha sorted after the numerical sort...but I just ran into this,
so apparently not.

Change-Id: Ifedf544222b5a8eb7630efda609eb6a5b9629de3

commit_message:
quota delete tenant_id parameter should be required

Makes the quota-delete tenant_id parameter required rather than
optional. Currently if not supplied it will pass 'None' as the tenant id
to the Nova API. It will be silently ignored (at least until
https://review.openstack.org/120971 has merged after which it will fail)
and no quota will be deleted.

Change-Id: I3ad8f36e92ed9ac54bf892f329ce3feb56f01be5
Closes-Bug: 1367127

[{'created': '2014-09-13 08:14:33.000000000', 'message': "check network ambiguity before external network auth

This change refactors the logic in the neutronv2 api to check for
network ambiguity before checking permission to attach external
network. In the scenario when there is a network available in the
client's tenant and an external shared network available in a
different tenant, the client was receiving a Forbidden error
because the external network was in the list of available networks
even though the client did have access to the other network in the
list.

With this change, the client receives a NetworkAmbiguous error instead
the same scenario, as they could succeed in booting an instance while
specifying --nic with the net-id of the network they can access.

"}]
commit_message:
check network ambiguity before external network auth

This change refactors the logic in the neutronv2 api to check for
network ambiguity before checking permission to attach external
network. In the scenario when there is a network available in the
client's tenant and an external shared network available in a
different tenant, the client was receiving a Forbidden error
because the external network was in the list of available networks
even though the client did have access to the other network in the
list.

With this change, the client receives a NetworkAmbiguous error instead
the same scenario, as they could succeed in booting an instance while
specifying --nic with the net-id of the network they can access.

Closes-Bug: #1364344

Change-Id: Ia94c25ff0ffd6a368da272fc6d883986156a0362

commit_message:
Fix EC2 instance type for a volume backed instance.

EC2 reports 'instance-store' type for a volume backed instance
which was booted with short root device name (no '/dev/' prefix).

This fix make instance type detection independent of addition
'dev' prefix to the instance root device name.

Change-Id: I6c2be09eaa91341e401bbc128b3efc79c60e345e
Closes-Bug: #1324400

representation of the compute_nodes and services table. The plan was
simply to add a host field to the compute_nodes table, populated with
the host value of the service that is related to the compute_node
record.

I did not want to change anything to do with the services table, nor did
I want to use this new compute_nodes.host field for anything in this
patch. This was just an attempt to try and change the terrible schema
underlying one of the most important tables in the database: the
compute_nodes table. The plan was to eventually detach the compute_nodes
table from the services table entirely, as the compute_nodes table is a
representation of the resources used/available on a provider of compute
resources, whereas the services table is merely a representation of the
message bus and communication status between a worker daemon and other
processes in the Nova system.

Unfortunately, trying to make even a tiny change like this results in
nearly 700 unit test failures, including random failures in things like
the os-hypervisors API extension "integrated" api_samples tests. The
output from this API extension should not have changed in the slightest,
and yet the failures come, and I have no idea how to diagnose, as the

in them.

and objects is THIS brittle, then I hold out little hope of us
addressing the real underlying problems in the resource tracker and
scheduler. Really looking for some assistance from some cores on
identifying why there are random crap failures in the integrated
api_samples tests here. Any held would be really appreciated.

Thanks,
-jay

commit_message:
Try putting host into compute_node table

So, this was the start of trying to un-cruft the awfulness that is the
representation of the compute_nodes and services table. The plan was
simply to add a host field to the compute_nodes table, populated with
the host value of the service that is related to the compute_node
record.

I did not want to change anything to do with the services table, nor did
I want to use this new compute_nodes.host field for anything in this
patch. This was just an attempt to try and change the terrible schema
underlying one of the most important tables in the database: the
compute_nodes table. The plan was to eventually detach the compute_nodes
table from the services table entirely, as the compute_nodes table is a
representation of the resources used/available on a provider of compute
resources, whereas the services table is merely a representation of the
message bus and communication status between a worker daemon and other
processes in the Nova system.

Unfortunately, trying to make even a tiny change like this results in
nearly 700 unit test failures, including random failures in things like
the os-hypervisors API extension "integrated" api_samples tests. The
output from this API extension should not have changed in the slightest,
and yet the failures come, and I have no idea how to diagnose, as the
api_samples tests are virtually impossible to diagnose wtf is going on
in them.

*sigh* Honestly, if the code around the compute_nodes and services table
and objects is THIS brittle, then I hold out little hope of us
addressing the real underlying problems in the resource tracker and
scheduler. Really looking for some assistance from some cores on
identifying why there are random crap failures in the integrated
api_samples tests here. Any held would be really appreciated.

Thanks,
-jay

Change-Id: I9e053221aa6493d7287965513b63a1b2223c9acb

[{'created': '2014-08-25 16:14:51.000000000', 'message': 'Fixes TypeError when instance fails to build

In some cases when a instance fails to build and is set in ERROR state
by the manager, we get the following error: "TypeError: string indices
must be integers, not str". This happens because the method that sets
the instance in ERROR state is wrongly called with instance.uuid
instead of the instace object.

This patch fixes the bug by calling the method with the proper instance
object

Change-Id: I95e9f9ed7b414227b19ee78006b7fa1a290bf97c
Closes-Bug: #1361256
'}]
commit_message:
Fixes TypeError when instance fails to build

In some cases when a instance fails to build and is set in ERROR state
by the manager, we get the following error: "TypeError: string indices
must be integers, not str". This happens because the method that sets
the instance in ERROR state is wrongly called with instance.uuid
instead of the instace object.

This patch fixes the bug by calling the method with the proper instance
object

Change-Id: I95e9f9ed7b414227b19ee78006b7fa1a290bf97c
Closes-Bug: #1361256

commit_message:
Set task_state for volume attach, detach, and swap

Adds task state values for attach_volume, detatch_volume,
and swap_volume operations so that conflicting operations
on the instance can be blocked via the check_instance_state
decorator.  Also record these operations in the instance_actions
table.

This also allow users to see slow volume operations are still in
progress.

Change-Id: I112071f9ed6b2cd3b40c0dea9218af4e7ec94260
Closes-Bug: #1275144

commit_message:
Remove PyPy from default tox runlist

PyPy has been failing locally for a month or two. On Ubuntu 14.04: 
"No module named _bsddb", on 12.04: "Not a .py file: 
/data/dev/work/ironic-python-agent/.tox/pypy/build/setuptools/
setuptools/cli-32.exe"

PyPy isn't enabled as a job in the gate yet (even non-voting). Until 
we sort the gate out and fix the above errors, we should remove it 
from the default tox runlist.

Change-Id: I34c0a72edebc296b79c6058e64ffb98f60979bcb

commit_message:
Update README with a bit more info

The information in README.rst is used to describe the python-ironicclient
package at pypi.python.org: https://pypi.python.org/pypi/python-ironicclient.

It doesn't have very much information right now. This adds a bit more
information; in particular, a link to the dev documentation.

Change-Id: Idb28b95b32617a325949c5f694d40b3834069d3f
Partial-Bug: #1314873

Only when a change really cannot be split in a reasonable way, it is fine to deliver it in one piece. But if possible, small changes would be better.

commit_message:
Extended intrinsic functions support.

Support get_property according to latest spec.
Support get_input.
Support recursive functions.
Process intrinsic functions in node template properties, interfaces,
capabilities and requirements.
Initialize node template properties and interfaces only once.
Removed inline importing of NodeTemplate in functions module.

Implements: blueprint tosca-ref-property

Change-Id: I363e1cc27791e6991d7e586c4e012b7ceed94490

commit_message:
Fix timestamp column migration

The updated_at and created_at columns from the baremetal database
table were being switched when migrated into the ironic database
table.

Change-Id: Ibc8b1d699fc302b84cf0bc2d8159a5b5510c3abb
Closes-Bug: #1369699

I remember during the discussion at the summit, one approach was talked about is to implement HA function as one 'flavor' of L3 service, for example, using service type framework. Is it something you want to consider?"}, {'account_id': 7183, 'date': '2014-01-22 06:37:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(1 inline comment)

I think creating admin network per tenant makes the L3 network node topology very complicated. There could be multiple tenants in L3 node and there will be multiple admin networks created for each tenant in current design. I understand the concern of how to choose existing networks on one router to be the admin network. How about making it configurable with the default value of random choosing one existing network as the admin network?

Also one comment on the l3_ha_net_cidr configuration."}, {'account_id': 7141, 'date': '2014-01-22 09:30:06.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

What do you think of creating one admin network per router instead of one admin network per tenant ?'}, {'account_id': 8873, 'date': '2014-01-22 15:39:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: (1 inline comment)

I proposed in an inline comment the possibility of forwarding VRRP traffic through a tenant network the router is a member of.'}, {'account_id': 5948, 'date': '2014-01-22 17:07:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

(7 inline comments)

"}, {'account_id': 7141, 'date': '2014-01-23 09:46:52.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7: (6 inline comments)

@Oled thanks for reviewing all my patches

@Gary
I think an extension better fits this need. In fact the current implementation doesn't add any functionalities in the user point of view and doesn't change the way that the virtual routers are handled, just instead of letting the l3 agent handled the interfaces directly, it delegates the management to keepalived. Moreover with an extension all plugins can leverage this improvement."}, {'account_id': 7141, 'date': '2014-01-23 13:53:14.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 8.'}, {'account_id': 8788, 'date': '2014-01-23 14:14:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: (1 inline comment)

Hi Itsuro,

The VRRP RFC specifies a shared mac address can be used by the active and the standby in order to avoid arp cache update and reduce the downtime. Only the active will get an IP.

What is your concern here ? could you elaborate a bit ?

With the regular mac learning it seems there is no issue here, our concern is more about dvr/l2pop.'}, {'account_id': 7141, 'date': '2014-08-05 11:31:36.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 54.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-05 11:31:42.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 54:

'}, {'created': '2014-08-24 17:56:10.000000000', 'message': "Add L3 VRRP HA base classes

Add L3 HA base classes on the plugin side. A new admin-only ha
attribute is added to the API router resource. Conversion from
or to HA router is possible. Each tenant gets a single network
used for HA traffic. The tenant_id for that network is set to
'' so that it isn't visible via the CLI or GUI. A new table
is added to map a tenant to its HA network. Specific HA
attributes are added to the extra router attributes table.
Finally, each HA router gets a port on the HA network, per
l3 agent it is scheduled on. A new table is added to track
these bindings.

DVR integration is not expected to work. Any issues will
be reported as bugs and handled after the feature merges.

DocImpact
Partially-implements: blueprint l3-high-availability

Change-Id: I9d935cf5e0c231e8cb7af5f61b9a9fc552c3521e

commit_message:
Add L3 VRRP HA base classes

Add L3 HA base classes on the plugin side. A new admin-only ha
attribute is added to the API router resource. Conversion from
or to HA router is possible. Each tenant gets a single network
used for HA traffic. The tenant_id for that network is set to
'' so that it isn't visible via the CLI or GUI. A new table
is added to map a tenant to its HA network. Specific HA
attributes are added to the extra router attributes table.
Finally, each HA router gets a port on the HA network, per
l3 agent it is scheduled on. A new table is added to track
these bindings. A new table is added in order to track
VRID allocations.

DVR integration is not expected to work. Any issues will
be reported as bugs and handled after the feature merges.
Migrating a router to HA or from HA works server side
but is not expected to work (Yet) agent side. This will be
dealt with as a bug in the future.

DocImpact
Partially-implements: blueprint l3-high-availability
Change-Id: I9d935cf5e0c231e8cb7af5f61b9a9fc552c3521e
Co-Authored-By: Assaf Muller <amuller@redhat.com>

commit_message:
Remove GPLv3 licensed apidocs javascript file

Trove's LICENSE file says it's Apache 2 licensed but
sh_main.js in the apidocs tree has a GPLv3 license in
it.

This removes the file with the GPLv3 license.

This doesn't appear to impact the API docs build.

Change-Id: I13d90dcc06b49511c4fabd3bd38555d9ec7771bd
Closes-Bug: #1358510

of the instance object but didn't add corresponding obj_make_compatible
calls for the new version. This adds the missing call.

commit_message:
[React] Rewriting Capacity with React

 - removed capacity template
 - created jsx file
 - table creation moved into separate react class

Related to blueprint backbone-to-react

commit_message:
Add --debug-logging parameter to devtest

We support passing a Debug parameter to our heat templates to set app
log levels to debug. Allow users of devtest to turn this on by passing
--debug-logging to devtest scripts.

Change-Id: I3f267f3d6290fddb40d80b1c889bade8980ddb43

commit_message:
Parameterize network type and tunnel types

Remove the hardcoding of gre as the Neutron tenant network type for the
Overcloud. This will enable the ability to deploy an Overcloud that uses
vxlan instead of gre tunnels. A new parameter, NeutronTunnelTypes, is
added to allow configuring the tunnel_types parameter in the Neutron ML2
configuration.

This change is required by https://review.openstack.org/#/c/92913

Change-Id: I2c2e2153a61349e58ada28c87aa2338c9f00e7bd

commit_message:
Use the server name attribute

The 'show' attribute results in a nova API call, which has
performance overhead even with attribute memoization.
The name attribute was added to expose the name without needing
an API call, since the resource already knows the name. This
change switches from using 'show' to 'name' throughout.

Change-Id: I1e83dd008cd02e5cec97868db0d5a695f07b7199

[{'created': '2014-09-15 03:44:33.000000000', 'message': 'Install ipset for the ml2 agent

Neutron recently added a new enable_ipset option which
helps optimize applying large iptables rules via the use
of ipset.

This patch installs the ipset package and enables the option
by default.
